WEBVTT

1
00:00:25,725 --> 00:00:28,421
[People Cheering, Chattering]

2
00:00:29,763 --> 00:00:31,754
[Man] "In the final moments
of a marathon...

3
00:00:31,865 --> 00:00:33,765
"two runners, 'A'and 'B',

4
00:00:33,867 --> 00:00:37,860
"Pass a point that is 100 meters from
the finish line at the same time...

5
00:00:37,971 --> 00:00:42,067
"and then run the final 100 meters
of the race at different constant speeds.

6
00:00:42,175 --> 00:00:44,200
"After the runners
pass the point...

7
00:00:44,310 --> 00:00:48,747
"'A'runs 80 meters
in the time 'B'runs 60 meters.

8
00:00:48,848 --> 00:00:53,444
How many meters will 'B'have left in the race
when 'A'reaches the finish line?"

9
00:00:53,553 --> 00:00:55,453
Let's see.

10
00:00:55,555 --> 00:00:59,218
Well, "A"is winning, right,
by 60... no, 80 meters...

11
00:00:59,325 --> 00:01:01,885
but at different
constant speeds.

12
00:01:01,995 --> 00:01:05,089
So "B"could catch up. I mean,
if B's constant speed...

13
00:01:05,198 --> 00:01:06,756
should somehow...

14
00:01:06,866 --> 00:01:09,061
But this could be
one of those trick questions.

15
00:01:09,169 --> 00:01:11,194
- [Siren Blares]
- "A"has to win, right? Yeah.

16
00:01:11,304 --> 00:01:15,240
"A"must win by...
Oh, God. Who knows?

17
00:01:15,341 --> 00:01:17,571
Oh, I don't know the answer.

18
00:01:17,677 --> 00:01:20,111
- [Thud]
- Hey!

19
00:01:20,213 --> 00:01:22,113
What the hell's going on here?

20
00:01:22,215 --> 00:01:24,513
Well, l-l-I'm no good
on the math part.

21
00:01:24,617 --> 00:01:26,448
You're a moron. It's easy!

22
00:01:26,553 --> 00:01:29,681
You should have been in the verbal section.
I have to think this over again.

23
00:01:29,789 --> 00:01:32,121
"Over again."
Forget it. I'm exhausted.

24
00:01:32,225 --> 00:01:34,523
I'll run it again.
You know, no problem.

25
00:01:34,627 --> 00:01:36,618
- You would.
- Give him a break.

26
00:01:36,729 --> 00:01:39,596
It's just some junior
sweating out his S.A.T.'s.

27
00:01:39,699 --> 00:01:41,826
Hey, who gives a shit?

28
00:01:41,935 --> 00:01:44,995
You got a problem? Afraid I'll win?
Is that what's happening?

29
00:01:45,105 --> 00:01:48,302
- You can't win. You're "B." You're never gonna win!
- Oh, really?

30
00:01:48,408 --> 00:01:52,936
You are a disgrace
to the entire alphabet.

31
00:01:53,046 --> 00:01:54,946
- Oh, really?
- Yeah.

32
00:01:55,048 --> 00:01:57,278
- Alphabetize this!
- [Groans]

33
00:01:58,785 --> 00:02:00,275
[Man]
Ladies and gentlemen...

34
00:02:00,386 --> 00:02:03,082
this is a shocking situation unfolding
at the finish line.

35
00:02:03,189 --> 00:02:06,181
And yet wasn't the outcome
entirely predictable...

36
00:02:06,292 --> 00:02:08,487
with our athletes
counting on...

37
00:02:09,562 --> 00:02:12,497
- Marlon Browne?
- Gosh, I'm sorry.

38
00:02:12,599 --> 00:02:15,193
You guys should have been
in Jessica Kailo's S.A.T.'s.

39
00:02:15,301 --> 00:02:17,496
You'd be drinking
Gatorade by now.

40
00:02:17,604 --> 00:02:20,300
Are you copying?

41
00:02:20,406 --> 00:02:22,465
Mm-mmm. Nope.
I'm fine. Thanks.

42
00:02:44,030 --> 00:02:47,158
[Sniffling]

43
00:02:56,242 --> 00:02:58,210
[Bell Rings]

44
00:02:59,879 --> 00:03:02,473
Okay, gang. That's all.
Let's go. Let's hand them in.

45
00:03:34,747 --> 00:03:36,647
Here you go, Mrs. Wyler.

46
00:03:36,749 --> 00:03:39,047
- How do you think you did, Marlon?
- I don't know.

47
00:03:39,152 --> 00:03:41,052
It's hard to tell
from a bunch of dots.

48
00:03:41,154 --> 00:03:44,612
Well, I'm sure you did fine.
I'm sure you did fine.

49
00:03:44,724 --> 00:03:46,919
Oh!

50
00:03:47,026 --> 00:03:50,393
It's nothing. Really.
Uh, h-have a good semester.

51
00:03:50,496 --> 00:03:51,064
Oh, dear.

52
00:03:51,064 --> 00:03:52,429
Oh, dear.

53
00:04:12,986 --> 00:04:17,719
[Man Singing]

54
00:04:23,896 --> 00:04:26,922
Are you gonna take
the S.A. T.'s again next month?

55
00:04:27,033 --> 00:04:31,163
I have to. With the scores I have now, I can
only get into the schools I'd never go to.

56
00:04:31,271 --> 00:04:33,102
Kel, it's one
overrated test.

57
00:04:33,206 --> 00:04:36,369
Yeah, well, you can say that, Jessica,
'cause you have really great scores.

58
00:04:36,476 --> 00:04:40,503
You guys, we gotta ease up. If we're this
crazy now, what's it gonna be like in April?

59
00:04:40,613 --> 00:04:43,309
I'm not gonna make it to April.
I know it.

60
00:04:43,416 --> 00:04:46,852
I heard about one girl who lost it so bad
she went into a mental institution.

61
00:04:46,953 --> 00:04:50,821
You mean the one that really cracked
and took off all her clothes in the interview?

62
00:04:50,923 --> 00:04:53,118
Oh, yeah.
Did you hear what happened?

63
00:04:53,226 --> 00:04:55,194
[Kel]
No.

64
00:04:57,130 --> 00:04:59,963
It was terrible because
when she went in for her interview...

65
00:05:00,066 --> 00:05:04,059
she was completely, totally prepared
to discuss the nuclear freeze...

66
00:05:04,170 --> 00:05:06,331
drug abuse,
violence in movies...

67
00:05:06,439 --> 00:05:09,272
all the important issues.

68
00:05:09,375 --> 00:05:11,570
But you know what
the interviewer did instead?

69
00:05:11,678 --> 00:05:13,475
He hit her with
a stress question.

70
00:05:13,579 --> 00:05:17,140
- Bastard.
- Just to watch her squirm, he asked...

71
00:05:17,250 --> 00:05:21,152
"If you could be any major household
appliance, which one would it be and why?"

72
00:05:21,254 --> 00:05:23,586
- [Groans]
- She blurted out "vacuum cleaner,"

73
00:05:23,690 --> 00:05:25,590
but couldn't back it up.

74
00:05:25,692 --> 00:05:27,626
It was all downhill
after that.

75
00:05:27,727 --> 00:05:29,786
No matter what she said,
he wasn't interested.

76
00:05:29,896 --> 00:05:32,558
Finally, he turns to her
and says...

77
00:05:32,665 --> 00:05:35,634
"Looks like
your time's up, miss...

78
00:05:35,735 --> 00:05:38,932
unless you have anything else interesting
you'd like to reveal about yourself."

79
00:05:39,038 --> 00:05:40,835
- And that's when she...
- [Gasps]

80
00:05:40,940 --> 00:05:44,341
Someone told me
she's still in the hospital.

81
00:05:44,444 --> 00:05:46,537
- No, she's dead.
- [Gasps]

82
00:05:46,646 --> 00:05:49,843
- Slit her wrists with the application form.
- That's how she did it?

83
00:05:51,718 --> 00:05:54,585
- Duh!
- [Sighs]

84
00:05:54,687 --> 00:05:56,587
Come on, you guys.
I was joking.

85
00:05:56,689 --> 00:05:59,920
Every year people pass around
these stories about the kid who cracked.

86
00:06:00,026 --> 00:06:01,926
Someone just made it up
to scare us.

87
00:06:02,028 --> 00:06:04,553
Yeah, well,
it worked for me. I'm scared.

88
00:06:04,664 --> 00:06:07,292
- I'm terrified.
- I think getting into college...

89
00:06:07,400 --> 00:06:09,493
is just like
any other campaign.

90
00:06:09,602 --> 00:06:11,900
And we just need
a little bit of strategy.

91
00:06:12,004 --> 00:06:16,600
That's why I asked my parents
to move to Montana... to help me
get into some east coast schools.

92
00:06:16,709 --> 00:06:19,644
- Well, I don't think it's that crazy.
- [Snickering]

93
00:06:19,746 --> 00:06:21,611
I'm sure gonna
miss my dog though.

94
00:06:24,684 --> 00:06:28,586
You're staring at me again, Marlon.
[Kissing Sounds]

95
00:06:28,688 --> 00:06:32,385
Don't do this, Oliver.
I'm weak from unrequited love.

96
00:06:32,492 --> 00:06:36,326
Talk to her about it and end this twisted
childhood obsession with Jessica Kailo.

97
00:06:36,429 --> 00:06:38,795
This is true love.
How many people do you know...

98
00:06:38,898 --> 00:06:40,991
who really end up with
their high school sweethearts?

99
00:06:41,100 --> 00:06:44,126
What are you gonna do?
Wait till you get to college to talk to her?

100
00:06:44,237 --> 00:06:48,173
I have seen a myriad of men come and go through
Jessica Kailo's life since the sixth grade.

101
00:06:48,274 --> 00:06:52,176
I am not going to make
those same mistakes. I'm committed.

102
00:06:52,278 --> 00:06:54,337
- You should be committed.
- I know.

103
00:06:54,447 --> 00:06:57,280
- I know. You have bigger plans.
- Of course I do.

104
00:06:57,383 --> 00:06:59,408
What's it gonna take
to convince you of that?

105
00:06:59,519 --> 00:07:02,613
Forget about
this "go to college" crap.

106
00:07:02,722 --> 00:07:05,714
What's wrong with
experiencing the real world?

107
00:07:05,825 --> 00:07:09,158
Look, we get out of high school,
we stick out our thumbs and pow!

108
00:07:09,262 --> 00:07:11,355
We got a four-year
jump on everybody.

109
00:07:11,464 --> 00:07:14,763
We may even run amok with
rebel game show hostesses...

110
00:07:14,867 --> 00:07:17,597
traveling the world
with unclaimed vacation prizes.

111
00:07:17,703 --> 00:07:20,171
I'm sorry, Oliver.
I don't buy into the theory...

112
00:07:20,273 --> 00:07:22,173
that on day one of real life...

113
00:07:22,275 --> 00:07:25,574
we stick out our thumbs and
pow... Vanna White picks us up...

114
00:07:25,678 --> 00:07:28,670
and drives us off into
a bright and exciting tomorrow.

115
00:07:28,781 --> 00:07:31,944
Well, I don't buy into the theory
that getting a college education...

116
00:07:32,051 --> 00:07:35,179
has gotta revolve entirely
around the possibility...

117
00:07:35,288 --> 00:07:38,052
ofJessica Kailo finally
giving you the time of day!

118
00:07:38,157 --> 00:07:40,216
[All Talking Stops]

119
00:07:42,128 --> 00:07:44,790
- It's 12:30.
- Thank you.

120
00:07:44,897 --> 00:07:46,797
Sure.

121
00:07:50,069 --> 00:07:52,037
[Jessica Laughing]

122
00:07:52,138 --> 00:07:54,129
[Jessica]
Here we go.

123
00:07:56,909 --> 00:08:00,538
Hi, Mrs. Elzwitt-Marcato-Hazelbaum.
I'm here to see Mrs. Wyler.

124
00:08:02,348 --> 00:08:04,339
- Oh.
- I'll be with you in a minute, Jessica.

125
00:08:04,450 --> 00:08:06,680
Okay, thanks,
Mrs. Wyler.

126
00:08:07,987 --> 00:08:09,887
Hi, Martin.

127
00:08:09,989 --> 00:08:12,753
Marlon... Browne.

128
00:08:12,859 --> 00:08:16,818
- Are you gonna vote for me?
- Oh, vote for you i-in the election.

129
00:08:16,929 --> 00:08:19,557
For class president.
Uh, of course, you don't have to.

130
00:08:19,665 --> 00:08:23,157
I would love to. Why don't you give me
a button, and I'll do publicity for you.

131
00:08:23,269 --> 00:08:25,669
- Buttons are a dollar.
- Mm-hmm.

132
00:08:25,771 --> 00:08:30,504
- Oh, all right.
- No, it's a joke. It's a joke.

133
00:08:31,911 --> 00:08:33,845
They're just kidding you.

134
00:08:36,048 --> 00:08:38,778
There you go.
It looks great.

135
00:08:38,885 --> 00:08:42,548
Why don't you give me some extra ones,
and I'll pass them out for you.

136
00:08:42,655 --> 00:08:45,055
Okay. I appreciate this.

137
00:08:45,157 --> 00:08:46,590
Okay, Jessica.

138
00:08:48,961 --> 00:08:51,054
When elected, Marlon,
I won't let you down.

139
00:08:52,398 --> 00:08:54,798
- Bye.
- Bye.

140
00:08:54,901 --> 00:08:56,835
- Hi.
- Hi.

141
00:08:56,936 --> 00:09:00,599
- So how was Italy, Jessica?
- Oh, it was great. It changed my life.

142
00:09:00,706 --> 00:09:03,800
Well, being an exchange student
looks super on your record.

143
00:09:03,910 --> 00:09:07,141
You'd be surprised how important
it is the way you spend your summers.

144
00:09:07,246 --> 00:09:09,476
It's getting insane.
Okay, let's see.

145
00:09:09,582 --> 00:09:13,882
Last spring your first choice
was Michigan.

146
00:09:13,986 --> 00:09:17,888
- My parents are alums. That's where they met.
- Michigan's an excellent school.

147
00:09:17,990 --> 00:09:20,788
- So what's the problem?
- I want to go to Ramsey College.

148
00:09:20,893 --> 00:09:23,225
[Gasps]
Ooh, goody! Ramsey.

149
00:09:24,797 --> 00:09:27,391
[Jessica] I met a group of kids
in Italy who go to Ramsey.

150
00:09:27,500 --> 00:09:29,400
They were on this
junior-year abroad program...

151
00:09:29,502 --> 00:09:31,595
in Venice to save the Italian frescoes
from pollution.

152
00:09:31,704 --> 00:09:35,140
While I was there, I realized
it's exactly the sort of thing I want to do.

153
00:09:35,241 --> 00:09:37,402
I mean, instead of being
a sorority girl...

154
00:09:37,510 --> 00:09:41,844
which is basically the direction
I've been headed in ever since... birth.

155
00:09:43,115 --> 00:09:45,242
Those kids are so cool.

156
00:09:45,351 --> 00:09:47,615
When they order spaghetti,
they call it pasta.

157
00:09:47,720 --> 00:09:50,280
I think you have a wonderful
chance to get into Ramsey.

158
00:09:50,389 --> 00:09:52,653
So apply there
and apply to Michigan.

159
00:09:52,758 --> 00:09:55,420
Right.

160
00:09:55,528 --> 00:09:58,497
- Here you go.
- Oh, thank you. Good luck.

161
00:09:58,598 --> 00:10:00,657
- Thanks. Bye.
- Bye.

162
00:10:05,037 --> 00:10:07,437
Do you have
an appointment, Marlon?

163
00:10:07,540 --> 00:10:10,532
Or did you just drop in?
Here. Come here.

164
00:10:10,643 --> 00:10:12,611
Bye-bye.

165
00:10:19,118 --> 00:10:23,748
So, Marlon, uh,
any specific college plan?

166
00:10:23,856 --> 00:10:26,654
- Well, you know Jessica Kailo.
- This Jessica Kailo?

167
00:10:26,759 --> 00:10:28,784
Mm-hmm. This Jessica Kailo.

168
00:10:28,894 --> 00:10:30,794
The same one that just left?

169
00:10:30,896 --> 00:10:33,865
Mm-hmm. My college plan
specifically...

170
00:10:33,966 --> 00:10:35,957
is to go wherever
she might be going.

171
00:10:36,068 --> 00:10:38,901
- That's your college plan?
- Mm-hmm.

172
00:10:39,005 --> 00:10:40,339
That's about the size of it.

173
00:10:40,339 --> 00:10:43,035
That's about the size of it.

174
00:10:43,142 --> 00:10:47,238
[Man] Our projections indicate that
we can expect over 8,000 applications...

175
00:10:47,346 --> 00:10:50,543
- for the 470 places in next year's class.
- [Man] Wow.

176
00:10:50,650 --> 00:10:53,915
In other words, that's almost
20 candidates for each available spot.

177
00:10:54,020 --> 00:10:57,046
Thanks, Sally. In other words,
it's a seller's market.

178
00:10:57,156 --> 00:10:59,852
- [Man] Hear, hear.
- Now, as usual...

179
00:10:59,959 --> 00:11:02,018
we are top-heavy
with students from both coasts.

180
00:11:02,128 --> 00:11:04,892
So for those of you
recruiting out west, eyes out...

181
00:11:04,997 --> 00:11:07,261
for that mythical kid
from Montana.

182
00:11:07,366 --> 00:11:09,926
[Woman Giggling]

183
00:11:10,036 --> 00:11:13,199
- Yes, Miss Saatchi, something funny?
- No. No, sir. I'm sorry.

184
00:11:13,305 --> 00:11:17,071
Oh, yes. And yesterday I received
this message from the music department.

185
00:11:17,176 --> 00:11:19,872
"Jesus, Bob, no more oboes."

186
00:11:19,979 --> 00:11:23,608
"No more oboes."Lock up their pencils.
That's one funny bunch.

187
00:11:23,716 --> 00:11:26,446
By the way, did everyone see
the poster Kip designed?

188
00:11:26,552 --> 00:11:28,918
Oh, yeah.
Hammett, the floor is yours.

189
00:11:29,021 --> 00:11:32,184
Okay, well, you know,
it's just our regular brochure...

190
00:11:32,291 --> 00:11:36,421
but unfolded,
it's an art-quality poster.

191
00:11:36,529 --> 00:11:39,123
Sally, can you help me?

192
00:11:39,231 --> 00:11:43,065
See. "At Ramsey, we're looking
beyond the numbers."

193
00:11:43,169 --> 00:11:46,764
[Coughs] But what does
it mean exactly?

194
00:11:46,872 --> 00:11:50,399
What it means, Flutter, is that, sure,
grades and S.A.T.'s are important to us...

195
00:11:50,509 --> 00:11:52,409
but people impress us more.

196
00:11:52,511 --> 00:11:54,376
We're sending a message.

197
00:11:54,480 --> 00:11:57,972
- Want to know the message
this poster is sending, Kip?
- No.

198
00:11:58,084 --> 00:12:03,249
[Scoffs] Bob, it sounds to me
like Ramsey has an inferiority complex.

199
00:12:03,355 --> 00:12:07,291
Come on. What's the problem?
Ramsey always gets great kids. I went here.

200
00:12:07,393 --> 00:12:09,554
Exactly.

201
00:12:09,662 --> 00:12:12,825
I think our message should be that
we're scrutinizing the numbers.

202
00:12:12,932 --> 00:12:17,665
So do I. We should be competitive
with all the top schools.

203
00:12:17,770 --> 00:12:20,068
Chancellor Holbrooke,
come in, please.

204
00:12:20,172 --> 00:12:22,504
Sit down, everyone.

205
00:12:23,909 --> 00:12:26,776
Is that a new suit?
It's your color, Mrs. Holbrooke.

206
00:12:26,879 --> 00:12:28,506
Thank you, Leo.

207
00:12:28,614 --> 00:12:33,074
[Bob] I think all of you know I'll be
moving on to another school next year.

208
00:12:33,185 --> 00:12:34,982
Chancellor Holbrooke will be
naming my replacement.

209
00:12:35,087 --> 00:12:37,749
I thought I would ask her
to say a few words.

210
00:12:37,857 --> 00:12:41,657
And those few words are I am looking
to promote from within.

211
00:12:41,761 --> 00:12:45,458
I also want to thank Bob for
the fine work he's done the last 17 years.

212
00:12:45,564 --> 00:12:49,398
The quality of our applicant pool
just gets better and better.

213
00:12:49,502 --> 00:12:52,938
Leo says this year's kids
should be off the charts.

214
00:12:53,038 --> 00:12:55,529
Thank you, Chancellor.
Joanna.

215
00:12:55,641 --> 00:13:01,204
This year we are going to
get killer kids...

216
00:13:01,313 --> 00:13:04,771
the kind of student that can
make it in the real world...

217
00:13:04,884 --> 00:13:07,409
the kind that can land
those high-paying jobs...

218
00:13:07,520 --> 00:13:10,353
and drive those big cars.

219
00:13:10,456 --> 00:13:14,552
- Like that B.M.W. You lease?
- I think my car sends a very strong message.

220
00:13:14,660 --> 00:13:18,289
And if I had designed
this poster, it might read... Sally...

221
00:13:18,397 --> 00:13:24,336
"Come to Ramsey, and one day
you too will own a B.M.W." Thank you, Sally.

222
00:13:24,436 --> 00:13:27,963
Now, that's a sentiment
that won't be lost...

223
00:13:28,073 --> 00:13:30,041
on today's
career-minded students.

224
00:13:30,142 --> 00:13:34,704
What about kids that aren't sentimental
about cars? Do we just reject all of them?

225
00:13:34,814 --> 00:13:37,146
Life's full
of rejection, Hammett.

226
00:13:37,249 --> 00:13:39,945
I think we're doing
the low-caliber applicant a favor...

227
00:13:40,052 --> 00:13:42,577
by letting them know that
right at the starting line.

228
00:13:44,089 --> 00:13:47,252
It's very painful to be
rejected by a college, Marlon...

229
00:13:47,359 --> 00:13:50,351
and you just don't have
the numbers to get into Ramsey.

230
00:13:50,462 --> 00:13:52,760
But I can take my S.A.T.'s
over again, right?

231
00:13:52,865 --> 00:13:55,834
And you should also
start trying to find some safeties...

232
00:13:55,935 --> 00:13:59,837
like maybe a state school
up in the Upper Peninsula.

233
00:13:59,939 --> 00:14:02,407
Jessica Kailo's applying there?

234
00:14:03,776 --> 00:14:06,040
Get out of here, Marlon.

235
00:14:06,145 --> 00:14:08,773
- Go. Leave. Be gone. Get out.
- Thank you, Miss Wyler.

236
00:14:08,881 --> 00:14:11,850
"At Ramsey, we're looking
beyond the numbers."

237
00:14:11,951 --> 00:14:14,442
I'm beginning to like
the sound of that, Kip.

238
00:14:14,553 --> 00:14:17,181
Yeah, it'll help us root out
the pigs, Flutter.

239
00:14:17,289 --> 00:14:20,190
Yeah, or any other barnyard animals
who are trying to apply.

240
00:14:20,292 --> 00:14:23,159
[Flutter] If you'd read that folder,
you'd have fallen for it too.

241
00:14:23,262 --> 00:14:27,198
Come on, Flutter. I mean,
the transcript read, "I am a pig."

242
00:14:27,299 --> 00:14:30,826
Irving Michael Anthony Pigg,
spelled P-I with a double "G."

243
00:14:30,936 --> 00:14:33,996
- It was a brilliant prank.
Would have fooled anyone.
- [Electronic Whirring]

244
00:14:34,106 --> 00:14:36,700
[Leo Scoffs]
It only fooled you, Flutter.

245
00:14:36,809 --> 00:14:39,607
Wait a minute.
Wait a minute.

246
00:14:40,646 --> 00:14:43,012
Okay. What is this?

247
00:14:43,115 --> 00:14:47,279
All right. A year ago I was tricked into
admitting a pig. I was made a fool of.

248
00:14:47,386 --> 00:14:49,616
Can't you let me
forget it, Leo?

249
00:14:49,722 --> 00:14:53,920
Come on. I mean, always hiding
these pigs in my office...

250
00:14:54,026 --> 00:14:55,789
Please.
[Groans]

251
00:14:55,895 --> 00:14:57,624
[Toy Squeaking]

252
00:14:57,730 --> 00:15:00,494
[Squeaking Continues]

253
00:15:00,599 --> 00:15:03,659
[Kip] It takes a special breed of
admissions officer to admit an animal.

254
00:15:03,769 --> 00:15:07,728
- Even one with all the numbers.
- The numbers are great. I've got 'em in my office.

255
00:15:07,840 --> 00:15:09,774
Hey, guys.
Coach Evans is looking for you.

256
00:15:09,875 --> 00:15:10,910
[All]
Coach Evans. Break!

257
00:15:10,910 --> 00:15:11,774
[All]
Coach Evans. Break!

258
00:15:11,877 --> 00:15:14,311
- [Whistle Blows]
- Hold it right there, you people.

259
00:15:14,413 --> 00:15:17,974
It makes me nervous when you boys
disappear behind closed doors.

260
00:15:18,083 --> 00:15:21,382
I end up with athletic chemists
and well-rounded political science majors...

261
00:15:21,487 --> 00:15:24,320
instead of somebody
who can run with a football.

262
00:15:24,423 --> 00:15:26,618
[Groans]
Hand off to you, Kip.

263
00:15:26,725 --> 00:15:28,989
- I've got a lunch with the chancellor.
- [Groans]

264
00:15:29,094 --> 00:15:31,255
Nice move.

265
00:15:31,363 --> 00:15:34,958
But you and I, we're gonna talk about it now,
goddamn it! Goddamn it!

266
00:15:35,067 --> 00:15:38,230
Nina! Coach, come on.
I give. Uncle. Uncle.

267
00:15:38,337 --> 00:15:41,602
Now, just in case you've forgotten
what they look like, this is an athlete.

268
00:15:41,707 --> 00:15:46,041
- Ronny "Sure Hands"Paulson?
- He's already the center of an all-out bidding war.

269
00:15:46,145 --> 00:15:49,114
Maybe we could just
mention a car this year... a small car.

270
00:15:49,214 --> 00:15:52,206
I mean, some schools are offering
stock portfolios, goddamn it.

271
00:15:52,318 --> 00:15:56,118
You'd better coordinate with Nina. She's
our man in charge of minority recruitment.

272
00:15:56,221 --> 00:15:58,382
This is not minority recruitment.
This is athletics.

273
00:15:58,490 --> 00:16:00,856
Look, this kid
can get in anywhere.

274
00:16:00,960 --> 00:16:02,985
I want someone
who needs Ramsey.

275
00:16:03,095 --> 00:16:07,191
Well, me too. But if he can
catch a goddamn football.

276
00:16:07,299 --> 00:16:10,132
[Chuckles]
See you, Coach.

277
00:16:13,772 --> 00:16:18,300
Why don't you just come with us to the college
fair and at least talk to the Ramsey people?

278
00:16:18,410 --> 00:16:20,378
- Oh, I should talk to the Ramsey people?
- Yeah.

279
00:16:20,479 --> 00:16:23,744
There are just about eight zillion kids
dying to get into Michigan.

280
00:16:23,849 --> 00:16:28,081
Your sisters went to Michigan.
They loved Michigan. They survived.

281
00:16:29,621 --> 00:16:32,089
Yeah, they all survived
ham pineapple surprise too, Dad.

282
00:16:32,191 --> 00:16:34,716
What's wrong with
ham pineapple surprise?

283
00:16:34,827 --> 00:16:38,228
Your sisters all
asked for the recipe.

284
00:16:38,330 --> 00:16:41,390
Dad, you know
I'm not like my sisters...

285
00:16:41,500 --> 00:16:43,593
and I'm ready to start
making my own decisions...

286
00:16:43,702 --> 00:16:45,897
with what I want to do
with my life, right?

287
00:16:46,005 --> 00:16:49,202
She wants to save
Italian frescoes.

288
00:16:49,308 --> 00:16:52,038
Oh, la santa Jessica.
How sweet.

289
00:16:52,144 --> 00:16:55,409
Did you ever think there might be something
else around here that needed saving?

290
00:16:55,514 --> 00:16:57,175
Did you ever go to
downtown Detroit?

291
00:16:57,282 --> 00:17:00,217
The whole place has to be
scraped and sprayed. It's polluted.

292
00:17:00,319 --> 00:17:02,787
- Come on, Dad. Be serious.
- I am serious, honey.

293
00:17:02,888 --> 00:17:06,153
Why should we pay $10,000
for you to go to Ramsey...

294
00:17:06,258 --> 00:17:08,283
when you can
go to Michigan for two?

295
00:17:08,394 --> 00:17:10,624
Come on. Is the football team
five times cuter?

296
00:17:10,729 --> 00:17:13,323
Do you get an education
that's five times better?

297
00:17:13,432 --> 00:17:16,196
I'll get a job. I'm already
looking into student loans.

298
00:17:16,301 --> 00:17:18,496
I really wish you'd decide
to come with.

299
00:17:21,373 --> 00:17:25,036
There's been a big change with student loans,
you know. They want to get paid back.

300
00:17:26,211 --> 00:17:28,202
Let's go.

301
00:17:29,314 --> 00:17:31,214
- Mom?
- What?

302
00:17:31,316 --> 00:17:34,410
- Is Dad really my father?
- Honey.

303
00:17:34,520 --> 00:17:36,488
Rah, rah, Ramsey.

304
00:17:37,723 --> 00:17:39,816
Okay, let's meet
those Ramsey people. Come on.

305
00:17:39,925 --> 00:17:42,018
Dad, are you really
gonna wear that hat?

306
00:17:42,127 --> 00:17:44,027
No, your mother's gonna
wear the hat.

307
00:17:44,129 --> 00:17:47,963
- Oh, George, we're so glad
you're keeping an open mind.
- Open wallet's more like it.

308
00:17:49,968 --> 00:17:54,337
College fair. College fair. You know, Jack
Kerouac never went to a college fair, Marlon.

309
00:17:54,440 --> 00:17:57,967
Oh, yeah? Well, he would have if he
knew Jessica Kailo was gonna be there.

310
00:17:58,077 --> 00:18:03,674
A great afternoon wasted on a boring,
uneventful and predictable formality.

311
00:18:03,782 --> 00:18:05,943
- Aaah!
- Aaah!

312
00:18:06,051 --> 00:18:08,315
- Aaah!
- Aaah!

313
00:18:08,420 --> 00:18:10,081
[Marching]

314
00:18:10,189 --> 00:18:13,022
Marlon, don't forget.
Safety first.

315
00:18:13,125 --> 00:18:15,025
Get plenty of safeties.

316
00:18:15,928 --> 00:18:17,862
- Aaah!
- Aaah!

317
00:18:19,131 --> 00:18:21,599
Lone Star State.
Y'all come in and check us out.

318
00:18:21,700 --> 00:18:24,362
- [All] Yeehaw!
- [Both Scream]

319
00:18:28,273 --> 00:18:29,797
Hi, boys.
What are your names?

320
00:18:29,908 --> 00:18:30,772
- Oliver.
- Marlon.

321
00:18:30,876 --> 00:18:31,604
Excuse me?

322
00:18:31,710 --> 00:18:32,608
- Oliver.
- Marlon.

323
00:18:32,711 --> 00:18:33,678
- What'd you say?
- Marlon.
- Oliver.

324
00:18:33,779 --> 00:18:34,939
I can't hear you, boy!

325
00:18:35,047 --> 00:18:36,139
- Oliver!
- Marlon!

326
00:18:36,248 --> 00:18:37,772
You girls want to
go to college?

327
00:18:37,883 --> 00:18:38,645
- No.
- Yeah.

328
00:18:38,750 --> 00:18:41,184
College is for pussies!

329
00:18:41,286 --> 00:18:43,618
- Hold it. Stop right there, students.
- [Both Scream]

330
00:18:43,722 --> 00:18:46,282
Do you believe in robotics
and artificial intelligence?

331
00:18:46,391 --> 00:18:49,827
- [Students] Yeah.!
- Then come along and follow me.

332
00:18:49,928 --> 00:18:51,862
Regard, Marlon,
the nerd factor...

333
00:18:53,198 --> 00:18:55,098
followed by
the Asian factor.

334
00:18:55,200 --> 00:18:58,692
All of us expected to play our roles according
to future needs of a planned economy.

335
00:18:58,804 --> 00:19:00,704
Hey, at least
we have a future.

336
00:19:00,806 --> 00:19:04,037
From what I hear,
Marlon could end up flipping hamburgers.

337
00:19:04,143 --> 00:19:08,011
How did he know? What, are my grades
posted on a bulletin board somewhere?

338
00:19:08,113 --> 00:19:09,740
- Aaah!
- Aaah!

339
00:19:16,155 --> 00:19:18,282
I'm glad you're interested
in us, Jessica...

340
00:19:18,390 --> 00:19:20,551
'cause Ramsey's a campus
full of real individuals.

341
00:19:20,659 --> 00:19:23,093
- That's great.
- Those are the people...

342
00:19:23,195 --> 00:19:26,187
you want to spend four years
of your life with?

343
00:19:26,298 --> 00:19:28,391
Maybe I should just go
over there alone.

344
00:19:28,500 --> 00:19:31,094
- Let me give you my card.
- Good luck.

345
00:19:35,607 --> 00:19:38,735
Please, give us a call, any of you,
if you have any questions.

346
00:19:38,844 --> 00:19:41,608
- Oh, thank you.
- I have a question, young man.

347
00:19:41,713 --> 00:19:43,806
[Clears Throat]
Is the pizza at Ramsey...

348
00:19:43,916 --> 00:19:46,111
- five times better than the pizza at Michigan?
- Daddy.

349
00:19:46,218 --> 00:19:49,676
I hope you'll answer that by coming
to our open house, Mr. Kailo.

350
00:19:49,788 --> 00:19:52,086
- Some of us will be there.
- We'll be there. Definitely.

351
00:19:52,191 --> 00:19:55,786
- Oh, yeah. Count on us.
- Thanks.

352
00:19:55,894 --> 00:19:58,624
Hi. Could I answer
any questions about Ramsey?

353
00:19:58,730 --> 00:20:02,791
Uh, no. No. This is the school
I wanted right here.

354
00:20:02,901 --> 00:20:04,300
[Mouthing Word]

355
00:20:05,571 --> 00:20:09,200
Welcome to
the Arcadia Bible Academy.

356
00:20:09,308 --> 00:20:14,974
Last night, Jesus Christ appeared to me
in a vision on a flaming pie...

357
00:20:15,080 --> 00:20:17,605
and he spoke unto me
and said, "I want..."

358
00:20:17,716 --> 00:20:19,616
What's your name?

359
00:20:19,718 --> 00:20:22,482
- Marlon.
- Marlon!

360
00:20:22,588 --> 00:20:26,046
"I want Marlon to attend
the Arcadia Bible Academy...

361
00:20:26,158 --> 00:20:28,456
payin' full tuition,
of course."

362
00:20:28,560 --> 00:20:31,154
Son, Jesus loves you.

363
00:20:31,263 --> 00:20:34,164
He might not if he saw
my S.A.T. Scores.

364
00:20:34,266 --> 00:20:36,166
- They're low?
- Low.

365
00:20:37,302 --> 00:20:39,270
All right.

366
00:20:39,371 --> 00:20:43,137
- Thanks anyway.
- Yeah. Jesus.

367
00:20:48,614 --> 00:20:50,878
[Sighs]

368
00:20:57,456 --> 00:21:00,152
I've been working at Ramsey
for about a year. I really enjoy it...

369
00:21:00,259 --> 00:21:02,193
Excuse me. Is it too late
to ask questions?

370
00:21:02,294 --> 00:21:04,728
No, no, no.
It's never too late.

371
00:21:04,830 --> 00:21:07,196
Choosing a college
is a major decision.

372
00:21:07,299 --> 00:21:09,199
Given some thought
to your educational goals?

373
00:21:09,301 --> 00:21:13,431
Well, personally speaking,
say, uh, I were in love with a girl...

374
00:21:13,538 --> 00:21:15,665
but obviously she wouldn't be
interested in me...

375
00:21:15,774 --> 00:21:18,868
until I had something more
to offer her and the world in general.

376
00:21:18,977 --> 00:21:22,003
I know that Ramsey would be
a good place for me to go and do that.

377
00:21:22,114 --> 00:21:25,447
- You want to go to college to broaden your mind.
- Right.

378
00:21:25,550 --> 00:21:27,882
Because you want to
win this girl.

379
00:21:27,986 --> 00:21:30,955
- Jessica Kailo.
- I talked toJessica Kailo.

380
00:21:31,056 --> 00:21:32,990
So have I. Once.

381
00:21:33,091 --> 00:21:35,423
"Once." You're following
a girl to college...

382
00:21:35,527 --> 00:21:37,552
you've talked to once.
[Chuckles]

383
00:21:37,663 --> 00:21:39,563
- Look, um...
- Marlon.

384
00:21:39,665 --> 00:21:43,226
Marlon. Marlon, do you think this is
the best way to plan your future?

385
00:21:43,335 --> 00:21:45,565
[Exhales]
Maybe not the best way...

386
00:21:45,671 --> 00:21:48,435
but people choose colleges
for all kinds of idiotic reasons...

387
00:21:48,540 --> 00:21:51,065
like fraternities and
Slavic language departments.

388
00:21:51,176 --> 00:21:53,474
Yeah, yeah, yeah,
but, uh, I gotta tell ya...

389
00:21:53,578 --> 00:21:56,376
trailing after
a girl is risky.

390
00:21:56,481 --> 00:21:59,109
Someone likeJessica Kailo,
l-l-I'm sure she has plans.

391
00:22:01,086 --> 00:22:03,646
On the other hand,
you're right. I mean...

392
00:22:03,755 --> 00:22:06,656
people have given me much worse reasons
for wanting to get into Ramsey.

393
00:22:06,758 --> 00:22:08,851
No kidding. I bet.

394
00:22:08,960 --> 00:22:11,360
Marlon, why don't you
just take my card.

395
00:22:11,463 --> 00:22:14,660
You and your parents
come to our open house. All right?

396
00:22:14,766 --> 00:22:18,031
Well, actually it's my dad
and my stepmother, and they're kind of busy.

397
00:22:18,136 --> 00:22:20,798
That's okay.
You come, then.

398
00:22:20,906 --> 00:22:22,999
- Really?
- Yeah.

399
00:22:23,108 --> 00:22:26,600
Wow. I really appreciate this,
Mr. Hammett.

400
00:22:26,712 --> 00:22:28,612
- You'll definitely be hearing from me.
- Okay.

401
00:22:28,714 --> 00:22:31,182
- Oh!
- [Chuckles]

402
00:22:33,385 --> 00:22:35,546
[Grunts]
Help.

403
00:22:37,122 --> 00:22:40,091
[Woman] Okay, Willie,
find the tetrahedron.

404
00:22:40,192 --> 00:22:44,128
- [Chuckles]
- No, that's a hexagon, sweetie.

405
00:22:44,229 --> 00:22:46,459
See? Count.

406
00:22:46,565 --> 00:22:49,090
[Together]
One, two, three...

407
00:22:49,201 --> 00:22:52,762
four, five, six.

408
00:22:52,871 --> 00:22:55,931
- Willie!
- Marlon.

409
00:22:56,041 --> 00:22:59,101
Airplane. Airplane.
Airplane. Airplane.

410
00:23:02,714 --> 00:23:06,616
All right. Give me your arm. Give me your leg.
[Imitates Engine Roaring]

411
00:23:06,718 --> 00:23:08,743
- I hate when he does that.
- So, Marlon...

412
00:23:08,854 --> 00:23:11,152
any progress on
the old college front?

413
00:23:11,256 --> 00:23:13,781
Yep. I talked to a guy
about a school today.

414
00:23:13,892 --> 00:23:16,554
- Which one? Harvard?
- [Chuckles]

415
00:23:16,661 --> 00:23:19,129
- No, Sharon.
- Mom.

416
00:23:19,231 --> 00:23:24,168
Call Sharon "Mom," Marlon.
Come on. Give it a try. Come on.

417
00:23:24,269 --> 00:23:26,169
No, Mom, it wasn't
old Harvard...

418
00:23:26,271 --> 00:23:28,205
or Stanford or even M.I.T.

419
00:23:28,306 --> 00:23:30,866
- It's Ramsey.
- Ramsey.

420
00:23:30,976 --> 00:23:32,944
- Where else did you look?
- Nowhere else.

421
00:23:33,044 --> 00:23:35,638
- For God's sakes.
- I thought the idea was to make a list.

422
00:23:35,747 --> 00:23:38,910
Of course it was.
A long, practical list.

423
00:23:39,017 --> 00:23:41,315
How many hundreds of colleges
were at that fair?

424
00:23:41,420 --> 00:23:44,753
How many thousands exist in this country
and you come up with a list of one?

425
00:23:44,856 --> 00:23:47,256
- And I don't think he'll get into there.
- Of course he won't.

426
00:23:47,359 --> 00:23:51,295
The thing about Ramsey, Dad, is that
they actually consider people like me.

427
00:23:51,396 --> 00:23:53,364
What does that mean?
They're searching for someone...

428
00:23:53,465 --> 00:23:55,933
with a definitive collection
of Silver Surfer comic books?

429
00:23:56,034 --> 00:23:58,264
This is not helpful.
Come on. Get out.

430
00:24:02,207 --> 00:24:04,175
I got this for you.

431
00:24:06,311 --> 00:24:09,769
"Bauer & Benedek College
Preparation Service"?

432
00:24:09,881 --> 00:24:14,215
Someone in Sharon's... your mom's...
aerobics class sent their kid there.

433
00:24:14,319 --> 00:24:16,810
I don't know. Maybe they can
do something for you.

434
00:24:16,922 --> 00:24:18,822
I want you to go, Marlon.

435
00:24:18,924 --> 00:24:22,018
- It's time you got your head out of the clouds.
- You're right, Dad.

436
00:24:22,127 --> 00:24:24,027
And it is. It's out.

437
00:24:24,129 --> 00:24:27,496
I made a valuable contact today,
and I really think that you should trust me.

438
00:24:30,235 --> 00:24:32,999
What does that mean, Bill?

439
00:24:33,104 --> 00:24:35,698
He'll still be
living at home next year?

440
00:24:49,588 --> 00:24:50,188
[Marlon] "In the middle
of a shark-infested harbor...

441
00:24:50,188 --> 00:24:51,883
[Marlon] "In the middle
of a shark-infested harbor...

442
00:24:51,990 --> 00:24:54,982
- two men, 'A'and 'B, '
strike a submerged boulder."
- Hey, we're gonna drown!

443
00:24:55,093 --> 00:24:57,061
Do something, you... you idiot!

444
00:24:57,162 --> 00:25:01,758
"Their crippled boat begins taking on water
at the rate of five gallons per minute.

445
00:25:01,867 --> 00:25:04,392
"If man 'A'can dump
two gallons per minute...

446
00:25:04,503 --> 00:25:06,937
"how much water
must man 'B'bail...

447
00:25:07,038 --> 00:25:10,735
to keep the 60-cubic-foot
boat from sinking?"

448
00:25:10,842 --> 00:25:13,606
- Oh, Jesus.
- What? What's going on?

449
00:25:13,712 --> 00:25:16,078
- It's that moron.
- Him?

450
00:25:16,181 --> 00:25:17,876
Oh, Christ.

451
00:25:17,983 --> 00:25:21,316
Oh, things are different
now that we're in the same boat, huh?

452
00:25:22,420 --> 00:25:24,388
