At least that way I could make
my decisions easy enough.

681
00:37:15,099 --> 00:37:17,067
My dear God.

682
00:37:19,203 --> 00:37:22,434
- Hi, I'm...
- Leo Whitman. [Chuckles]

683
00:37:22,540 --> 00:37:25,236
We met at the Carlsborough Academy
alumni tea, Dr...

684
00:37:25,343 --> 00:37:27,573
- Dr. PhillipJellinek.
- Jellinek. That's right.

685
00:37:27,678 --> 00:37:30,272
- PhillipJellinek, Jr.
- Yes, you are, and welcome to Ramsey.

686
00:37:30,381 --> 00:37:32,611
It's incredible.

687
00:37:32,717 --> 00:37:35,083
The girls' dorm is this way,
and over that way...

688
00:37:35,186 --> 00:37:39,885
And you still think it will be the same around
here with Leo as the dean of admissions.

689
00:37:39,991 --> 00:37:42,425
[Scoffs]
I don't want to be dean of admissions.

690
00:37:42,526 --> 00:37:45,290
All right. But what's it
going to be like working for him?

691
00:37:45,396 --> 00:37:47,956
- [Horn Honking]
- [Whistle Blows]

692
00:37:48,065 --> 00:37:49,760
Oh, wow. Wow.
Look who's here.

693
00:37:49,867 --> 00:37:52,665
We got Ronny "Sure Hands" Paulson
here, goddamn it.

694
00:37:52,770 --> 00:37:56,103
- Hi, Ronny.
- Hello, Miss Saatchi. I'll bet
you're surprised to see us.

695
00:37:56,207 --> 00:38:00,041
I'll admit, a little.
Dean, this is Ronny Paulson.

696
00:38:00,144 --> 00:38:02,339
And this is Ronny's lawyer,
Dan Bestman.

697
00:38:02,446 --> 00:38:05,779
- We were supposed to bring a lawyer?
- [All] Shit.

698
00:38:05,883 --> 00:38:07,783
[Man Singing]

699
00:38:14,725 --> 00:38:17,660
So how have you found Ramsey so far?

700
00:38:17,762 --> 00:38:20,287
- I took the bus, remember?
- [Chuckles]

701
00:38:20,398 --> 00:38:22,298
No. Really,
Miss Saatchi, I'm fine.

702
00:38:22,400 --> 00:38:24,368
I appreciate
your time and concern...

703
00:38:24,468 --> 00:38:26,868
but you should be out
enjoying yourself.

704
00:38:26,971 --> 00:38:29,872
It's not exactly me
you should be baby-sitting.

705
00:38:31,676 --> 00:38:35,874
Oh, you're right. I have to go
baby-sit the love of my life. Excuse me.

706
00:38:35,980 --> 00:38:38,141
I'm sure I'll be just fine.

707
00:38:39,383 --> 00:38:42,079
- [Together] Hi.
- I was wrong.

708
00:38:42,186 --> 00:38:44,086
What is this atrocity?

709
00:38:44,188 --> 00:38:46,986
[Kip]
Welcome, Ramsey hopefuls.

710
00:38:49,427 --> 00:38:52,021
- We're theJellineks.
- Oh, yes. You certainly are.

711
00:38:53,631 --> 00:38:55,758
So, are you just dropping off
young Jellinek?

712
00:38:55,866 --> 00:38:57,857
- Why would I do that?
- See, sir, it's, uh...

713
00:38:57,968 --> 00:38:59,936
it's kind of
a kids' get-together.

714
00:39:00,037 --> 00:39:02,972
They can kind of unwind
without the parents around...

715
00:39:03,074 --> 00:39:05,542
and get a feel
for the social life here at Ramsey.

716
00:39:05,643 --> 00:39:07,543
- Social life?
- Yeah.

717
00:39:07,645 --> 00:39:10,842
- Social disease is more like it.
- Why don't you look around, have some food...

718
00:39:10,948 --> 00:39:12,882
and spread your warmth.

719
00:39:12,983 --> 00:39:14,883
Making, uh,
new friends here?

720
00:39:14,985 --> 00:39:17,954
See the world, Vera.
Smash out of this coffin...

721
00:39:18,055 --> 00:39:20,387
they call a college experience
before they shut the lid.

722
00:39:20,491 --> 00:39:24,860
How very uplifting, Oliver. Ever thought about
entertaining sick kids in hospitals?

723
00:39:24,962 --> 00:39:27,863
Oliver takes his college-free future
very seriously.

724
00:39:27,965 --> 00:39:31,128
He's looking to travel the world
with renegade game show hostesses.

725
00:39:31,235 --> 00:39:35,228
Sounds like your run-of-the-mill American
dream. What are you looking for, Marlon?

726
00:39:42,413 --> 00:39:44,313
It just walked in.

727
00:39:45,750 --> 00:39:48,719
[Singing Continues]

728
00:39:51,922 --> 00:39:54,447
Hey, Marlon Browne.
You made it.

729
00:39:54,558 --> 00:39:56,958
Barely. We took Oliver's car.

730
00:39:57,061 --> 00:39:58,995
Ramsey's wonderful.

731
00:39:59,096 --> 00:40:01,894
I just have this feeling that I'm
gonna ace my interview tomorrow.

732
00:40:01,999 --> 00:40:04,559
- It's the only school I want to go to.
- Funny thing.

733
00:40:04,668 --> 00:40:06,966
L-I suddenly think Ramsey
might be in my stars also.

734
00:40:07,071 --> 00:40:10,006
Marlon, it's
the real world now.

735
00:40:11,776 --> 00:40:14,267
Marlon, you're different.

736
00:40:14,378 --> 00:40:17,142
Y-You mean, like different
different, or like Elephant Man different?

737
00:40:17,248 --> 00:40:19,910
No, no, I mean good different.
You're not geeky.

738
00:40:20,017 --> 00:40:23,043
- I mean you're not the way
I thought you were at school.
- Yeah, well...

739
00:40:23,154 --> 00:40:25,054
this is a preview
of the college me.

740
00:40:25,156 --> 00:40:28,125
- There's four more years of this
to come if you're interested.
- [Chuckles]

741
00:40:30,461 --> 00:40:33,988
Just make a decision, Jess. I mean, they're not
gonna accept you or not accept you...

742
00:40:34,098 --> 00:40:36,532
- based on your shoes.
- You need to stand out, Mom.

743
00:40:36,634 --> 00:40:40,434
Every detail counts. Which do you think
I should wear, Reeboks or my loafers?

744
00:40:40,538 --> 00:40:42,438
Your Reeboks.

745
00:40:42,540 --> 00:40:45,634
Okay, but that could make me look
too frivolous and not intellectual enough.

746
00:40:45,743 --> 00:40:50,180
- Why don't you wear your Reeboks
and show them your loafers?
- Mom.

747
00:40:50,281 --> 00:40:54,012
Oh, honey. Wear your Reeboks.
Go for it. What the hell.

748
00:40:54,118 --> 00:40:57,451
Good luck.
We're very proud of you.

749
00:41:07,298 --> 00:41:10,461
[Leo] I'm sorry. I have no idea.
I'll find out why this happened.

750
00:41:10,568 --> 00:41:12,559
I promise you, sir,
heads will roll. Trust me.

751
00:41:12,670 --> 00:41:16,299
L-I can't believe someone would be
so insensitive as to make this mistake.

752
00:41:16,407 --> 00:41:19,638
Sally, there's been a grievous mistake.
This is Mr. Jellinek.

753
00:41:19,743 --> 00:41:23,406
Dr. Jellinek.
I'm PhillipJellinek, Jr.

754
00:41:23,514 --> 00:41:26,074
- Sally, for some ungodly reason,
- My pleasure.

755
00:41:26,183 --> 00:41:29,016
Phillip here has been scheduled
to interview with Flutter.

756
00:41:29,119 --> 00:41:33,488
- Yeah? So what?
- It really doesn't matter
who conducts the interviews.

757
00:41:33,591 --> 00:41:35,684
If it doesn't matter,
we'll see Dean Patterson.

758
00:41:35,793 --> 00:41:37,761
No. His schedule
is already overloaded.

759
00:41:37,862 --> 00:41:39,921
Overload...

760
00:41:40,030 --> 00:41:43,522
Oh, Sally.
Can I have a word with you?

761
00:41:43,634 --> 00:41:46,398
Well, if there's anything
I can help you with, uh...

762
00:41:46,504 --> 00:41:48,529
questions about the courses...

763
00:41:48,639 --> 00:41:50,197
accom... modations?

764
00:41:50,307 --> 00:41:52,537
- Anything at all.
- Sally...

765
00:41:52,643 --> 00:41:54,838
they met with the dean
at Princeton and Yale...

766
00:41:54,945 --> 00:41:58,574
not some 4-H club reject
like Flutter.

767
00:41:58,682 --> 00:42:01,207
Flutter is the guy
who only sees the people...

768
00:42:01,318 --> 00:42:04,776
who are like...
bleeding-heart fresco savers.

769
00:42:04,889 --> 00:42:06,823
You know,
socially-correct cheerleaders...

770
00:42:06,924 --> 00:42:10,485
that are elected class president in spite of
the fact that they can't even decide...

771
00:42:10,594 --> 00:42:13,563
which shoes to wear when they
leave the house without talking to Mommy.

772
00:42:13,664 --> 00:42:18,465
TheJellineks are Ramsey legacy, for God sakes,
and you've got 'em scheduled with Flutter.

773
00:42:18,569 --> 00:42:21,129
Leo, calm down.
I will see what I can do.

774
00:42:21,238 --> 00:42:23,138
Good.

775
00:42:23,240 --> 00:42:26,767
- All set, sir. Nothing to worry about.
- Good. We'll see the dean.

776
00:42:26,877 --> 00:42:29,607
I didn't travel 400 miles
to see underlings.

777
00:42:29,713 --> 00:42:33,205
Let the rest of these people
be seen by underlings...

778
00:42:33,317 --> 00:42:35,615
- like that girl in the Reeboks there.
- [Leo] Her?

779
00:42:35,719 --> 00:42:39,621
[Chuckles] Girls like her
are a dime a dozen.

780
00:42:39,723 --> 00:42:43,124
She's state college material
at best.

781
00:42:44,995 --> 00:42:47,486
Let's go inside.

782
00:42:47,598 --> 00:42:50,328
"Dime a dozen"?

783
00:43:06,383 --> 00:43:09,284
- Hi.
- Hi.

784
00:43:09,386 --> 00:43:13,152
See her? I bet she has
a 3.5 grade average.

785
00:43:13,257 --> 00:43:16,590
- Yeah? How do you know?
- Oh, almost everybody here does...

786
00:43:16,694 --> 00:43:20,596
- with about a combined 1350 on their S.A.T.'s.
- Oh, me too.

787
00:43:20,698 --> 00:43:25,294
- So, are there many people here
on the yearbook staff?
- Oh, billions.

788
00:43:25,402 --> 00:43:27,700
- I'm editor of mine.
- Oh.

789
00:43:27,805 --> 00:43:32,174
I'm just activity reporter of mine. I didn't
want it to interfere with my cheerleading.

790
00:43:32,276 --> 00:43:36,144
Well, my cheerleading practice
comes before school.

791
00:43:36,246 --> 00:43:40,512
Well, that wouldn't work for me because I have
class meetings in the morning and I'm president.

792
00:43:40,618 --> 00:43:43,178
- Although you're probably class president also.
- No, vice president.

793
00:43:43,287 --> 00:43:48,054
- That's an important job. I mean,
in case the president dies.
- My sister is president.

794
00:43:48,158 --> 00:43:50,353
- Laurie.
- Terrie.

795
00:43:50,461 --> 00:43:52,861
- We better go practice.
- We have a special audition...

796
00:43:52,963 --> 00:43:54,897
With the music
department.

797
00:43:54,999 --> 00:43:57,092
Great. What instrument
do you play?

798
00:43:57,201 --> 00:43:59,101
- The violin.
- The oboe.

799
00:43:59,203 --> 00:44:02,695
- She plays the oboe.
- She plays the violin. Anyway, we better get going.

800
00:44:02,806 --> 00:44:05,570
- [Together] Good luck.
- Bye.

801
00:44:13,217 --> 00:44:15,185
Excuse me.

802
00:44:19,289 --> 00:44:21,450
[Sighs]

803
00:44:36,840 --> 00:44:38,808
[Sally]
Jessica Kailo.

804
00:44:40,511 --> 00:44:42,672
[Whimpers]

805
00:44:46,283 --> 00:44:50,014
- [Buzzer Buzzes]
- Jessica Kailo's coming in, Mr. Flutter.

806
00:44:50,120 --> 00:44:52,782
Oh, send her in, Sally.

807
00:44:57,194 --> 00:44:59,685
- [Knocking On Door]
- Uh, come in.

808
00:44:59,797 --> 00:45:01,458
Come in.
[Groans]

809
00:45:04,301 --> 00:45:06,070
Oh, excuse me.
I'm Jessica Kailo, Mr. Flutter.

810
00:45:06,070 --> 00:45:07,731
Oh, excuse me.
I'm Jessica Kailo, Mr. Flutter.

811
00:45:07,838 --> 00:45:09,738
Oh, Jessica,
how are you?

812
00:45:09,840 --> 00:45:12,274
I'm... I'm fine. Thanks.
And you?

813
00:45:12,376 --> 00:45:15,140
Well, I've hurt my hand,
but I'm fine.

814
00:45:15,245 --> 00:45:17,543
- Would you like to sit down, Julie.
- Jessica.

815
00:45:17,648 --> 00:45:19,707
- Jessica. Yeah, fine.
- [Toy Squeaks]

816
00:45:20,718 --> 00:45:24,154
[Squeaking Continues]

817
00:45:24,254 --> 00:45:26,654
- Would you like a cup of coffee?
- Yes. Thank you.

818
00:45:29,593 --> 00:45:31,788
- Oh! I'm sorry.
- [Cup Shatters]

819
00:45:31,895 --> 00:45:34,989
Um, gotta go. See you.

820
00:45:36,834 --> 00:45:39,496
Marlon Browne.
10:00 interview.

821
00:45:39,603 --> 00:45:41,230
Terrific. Have a seat.

822
00:45:43,874 --> 00:45:46,138
I was an exchange student
last summer.

823
00:45:46,243 --> 00:45:48,404
So I learned quite a bit
of Italian.

824
00:45:50,714 --> 00:45:52,648
Uh, y-yes.
And where were you?

825
00:45:52,750 --> 00:45:55,844
- Where was I?
- Yes. Where did you study Italian?

826
00:45:56,687 --> 00:45:59,986
- In Italy.
- Oh. Yes.

827
00:46:00,090 --> 00:46:02,024
[Chuckles]

828
00:46:02,126 --> 00:46:06,085
Uh, in Italy, I met a lot of
interesting people while I was studying there.

829
00:46:06,196 --> 00:46:08,824
Some of them were involved
in saving the Italian frescoes.

830
00:46:08,932 --> 00:46:10,991
Those are paintings.

831
00:46:11,101 --> 00:46:13,365
Oh. Yes, of course.

832
00:46:13,470 --> 00:46:16,132
- [Thinking] He's bored. I'm losing him.
- Go on. Go on.

833
00:46:16,240 --> 00:46:18,674
I think one of
the most significant...

834
00:46:18,776 --> 00:46:21,711
[Thinking] He's totally not interested.
He's... He's ignoring me.

835
00:46:21,812 --> 00:46:25,043
He's cleaning his closets
while I'm dying a thousand deaths.

836
00:46:25,149 --> 00:46:27,845
I'm completely blowing this.

837
00:46:27,951 --> 00:46:29,942
All the old hand-carved animals.

838
00:46:30,053 --> 00:46:32,021
Uh, horses, tigers...

839
00:46:32,122 --> 00:46:34,386
ostriches, pigs...

840
00:46:34,491 --> 00:46:36,686
Pigs? Why did you say that?

841
00:46:36,794 --> 00:46:40,252
- I don't know why.
- Oh.

842
00:46:40,364 --> 00:46:44,061
Well, you know,
pigs are very interesting animals.

843
00:46:44,168 --> 00:46:47,160
One very famous literary figure
kept pigs as pets.

844
00:46:47,271 --> 00:46:50,570
- Do you know who that was?
- [Thinking] Stress question, stress question.

845
00:46:50,674 --> 00:46:53,074
- No.
- He was Gertrude Stein.

846
00:46:53,177 --> 00:46:55,907
- Oh.
- [Toy Squeaking]

847
00:47:01,585 --> 00:47:03,815
Uh... [Clears Throat]
I was also involved...

848
00:47:03,921 --> 00:47:05,684
in a lot of other activities
at school...

849
00:47:05,789 --> 00:47:07,313
- [Toy Squeaking]
- Yearbook staff...

850
00:47:07,424 --> 00:47:10,222
uh, World Affairs Council...

851
00:47:10,327 --> 00:47:13,160
um, Honor Society.

852
00:47:13,263 --> 00:47:15,254
What's this?

853
00:47:15,365 --> 00:47:18,027
Oh, uh, that's my watch.

854
00:47:18,135 --> 00:47:22,663
Well, I see our time
is just about up, Julie.

855
00:47:22,773 --> 00:47:25,139
- Jessica.
- Jessica.

856
00:47:25,242 --> 00:47:27,142
- Okay, great.
- [Toy Squeaks]

857
00:47:27,244 --> 00:47:30,213
- So my interview's over with.
- Unless there's something else...

858
00:47:30,314 --> 00:47:32,214
you would like to reveal
about yourself.

859
00:47:32,316 --> 00:47:35,012
Unless I have anything else
I'd like to reveal about myself?

860
00:47:35,118 --> 00:47:39,054
Yes. Unless you have anything else
you'd like to reveal about yourself.

861
00:47:39,156 --> 00:47:42,523
[Thinking] Reveal about myself?
Reveal about myself?

862
00:47:42,626 --> 00:47:44,685
Reveal myself.
Reveal myself.

863
00:47:46,630 --> 00:47:49,690
Anything else I'd like to
reveal about myself?

864
00:47:49,800 --> 00:47:53,065
Is there anything else
I'd like to reveal about myself?

865
00:47:54,304 --> 00:47:55,771
[Screams]

866
00:47:58,775 --> 00:48:00,675
- Shit!
- Whoa!

867
00:48:00,777 --> 00:48:03,041
I'll never
get accepted here.

868
00:48:03,146 --> 00:48:05,080
[Sobbing]

869
00:48:06,650 --> 00:48:08,550
Jessica?

870
00:48:09,653 --> 00:48:11,883
Marlon, your appointment.

871
00:48:11,989 --> 00:48:13,889
There's no rescheduling, pup.

872
00:48:13,991 --> 00:48:16,050
Pup, pup, pup. Puppy.

873
00:48:17,160 --> 00:48:19,060
Jessica, how you doin'?

874
00:48:19,162 --> 00:48:22,689
Marlon, if you don't mind, I really
don't feel like talking right now.

875
00:48:22,799 --> 00:48:25,859
Oh, sure. No problem. We can always
talk later in school or something.

876
00:48:25,969 --> 00:48:28,938
- Or maybe next year here at Ramsey.
- I won't be here next year.

877
00:48:29,039 --> 00:48:30,973
I'm not right
for this school.

878
00:48:31,074 --> 00:48:33,065
Come on. You?
You're perfect...

879
00:48:33,176 --> 00:48:36,475
- for Ramsey.
- Everyone here is perfect. Haven't you noticed?

880
00:48:36,580 --> 00:48:38,514
I blew it. I had
a terrible interview.

881
00:48:38,615 --> 00:48:40,515
[Scoffs] Jesus.
Interviews don't matter.

882
00:48:40,617 --> 00:48:43,142
I just blew mine completely,
coming out here. How about that?

883
00:48:43,253 --> 00:48:47,189
- I thought you said the interview
was gonna be the key for you.
- Sure, they matter a little.

884
00:48:47,291 --> 00:48:51,728
But it's not like high school, where if you make
a mistake you get branded as a moron for life.

885
00:48:51,828 --> 00:48:54,490
- It's no big deal at a place like Ramsey.
- How do you know?

886
00:48:55,799 --> 00:48:57,767
Trying things out
is what happens at college.

887
00:48:57,868 --> 00:49:01,599
You get a great chance to start all over again,
just when most people need to.

888
00:49:01,705 --> 00:49:05,334
It's like a federal protection
and relocation program for teenagers.

889
00:49:05,442 --> 00:49:08,036
You don't know how bad it was.

890
00:49:08,145 --> 00:49:10,670
Nothing could be that bad.

891
00:49:10,781 --> 00:49:14,012
- It was awful. Trust me.
- But awful enough to ruin your chances?

892
00:49:14,117 --> 00:49:16,176
You would have to
do something really idiotic...

893
00:49:16,286 --> 00:49:18,777
like expose yourself
or something.

894
00:49:20,190 --> 00:49:22,454
Marlon, leave me alone,
all right?

895
00:49:27,230 --> 00:49:29,130
Something happened
with her interview...

896
00:49:29,232 --> 00:49:32,326
and she has locked herself in her hotel room
and won't talk to anyone.

897
00:49:32,436 --> 00:49:34,768
- I think something really terrible has happened.
- I'm sorry...

898
00:49:34,871 --> 00:49:37,499
but there is no way
I could show you her files.

899
00:49:37,607 --> 00:49:39,871
They're strictly
confidential.

900
00:49:39,977 --> 00:49:43,276
I know, but now she's considering
not even applying to Ramsey.

901
00:49:43,380 --> 00:49:45,814
[Sighs] This choosing a college
because of a girl...

902
00:49:45,916 --> 00:49:47,816
maybe we should
discuss that idea.

903
00:49:47,918 --> 00:49:49,818
- We did once before.
- Yeah? What'd I say?

904
00:49:49,920 --> 00:49:53,253
- You said you'd heard a lot of worse reasons.
- Are you in love with Jessica?

905
00:49:54,858 --> 00:49:58,589
Then screw it.
Love is a fuckin'noble emotion...

906
00:49:58,695 --> 00:50:01,994
but Ramsey is not gonna admit you
based on your feelings for a girl.

907
00:50:02,099 --> 00:50:04,727
- You've gotta forget her.
- Forget her?

908
00:50:04,835 --> 00:50:07,770
Let me worry
aboutJessica Kailo.

909
00:50:07,871 --> 00:50:10,738
You concentrate on
your own application, okay?

910
00:50:10,841 --> 00:50:12,741
[Sighs]
Okay.

911
00:50:12,843 --> 00:50:15,403
This is terrific, Mr. Hammett.
Just great.

912
00:50:15,512 --> 00:50:18,037
- Thanks so much.
- Sure.

913
00:50:18,148 --> 00:50:20,946
I really appreciate this.
God, this is just great.

914
00:50:21,051 --> 00:50:23,042
[Kip] My vote can't
be bought there, Marlon.

915
00:50:23,153 --> 00:50:25,451
Thanks. Okay.

916
00:50:25,555 --> 00:50:27,455
- Thanks again.
- Ooh. Ouch.

917
00:50:28,658 --> 00:50:30,558
Yeah.

918
00:50:32,796 --> 00:50:35,356
- [Knocking On Door]
- Come in.

919
00:50:41,738 --> 00:50:44,206
I heard you wanted to
talk to me, Mr. Hammett.

920
00:50:44,307 --> 00:50:46,707
Oh, yeah. Hi, Jessica.
Come on in.

921
00:50:46,810 --> 00:50:48,903
I wanted to talk to you
before you left.

922
00:50:49,012 --> 00:50:50,912
Hi. Sit down.

923
00:50:51,014 --> 00:50:52,914
- How are ya?
- Hi.

924
00:50:53,016 --> 00:50:57,077
I heard you were kind of upset after
your interview with Mr. Flutter yesterday.

925
00:50:57,187 --> 00:51:00,588
Mr. Hammett, I'd rather not
talk about that right now.

926
00:51:00,690 --> 00:51:03,625
Look, l... I know
you feel vulnerable.

927
00:51:03,727 --> 00:51:05,627
I mean, you just
open yourself up...

928
00:51:05,729 --> 00:51:09,665
to a perfect stranger,
probably for the first time.

929
00:51:09,766 --> 00:51:11,666
But, look,
it's just an interview...

930
00:51:11,768 --> 00:51:14,931
and you were not being judged
on what you have or what you don't have.

931
00:51:15,038 --> 00:51:18,337
I know. You think the littlest things
are a big deal...

932
00:51:18,442 --> 00:51:20,603
but, believe me,
really they're not.

933
00:51:20,710 --> 00:51:22,507
Okay. We've seen it all before.

934
00:51:22,612 --> 00:51:25,945
And Mr. Flutter,
he felt that you were an extremely...

935
00:51:26,049 --> 00:51:28,415
well-rounded young lady.

936
00:51:28,518 --> 00:51:30,418
Oh, God!

937
00:51:30,520 --> 00:51:32,147
[Door Closes]

938
00:51:37,527 --> 00:51:40,223
Ooh, ooh, ooh, ooh.

939
00:51:40,330 --> 00:51:43,299
- Uh-huh.
- Pomona, can you hold?
I have Duke on the other line.

940
00:51:43,400 --> 00:51:45,960
Duke, can you hold?
I have Georgetown on the other line.

941
00:51:46,069 --> 00:51:49,129
I know you're disappointed, Chancellor Smith.
His application was fabulous.

942
00:51:49,239 --> 00:51:52,868
We're counselors, not his parents. What can
we do if he didn't choose your school?

943
00:51:52,976 --> 00:51:55,968
Oxford? Please hold. I have
Seven Sisters Colleges on the other line.

944
00:51:56,079 --> 00:51:58,946
Girls, I'll call you back.
I have a very important client.

945
00:51:59,049 --> 00:52:01,313
- Okay, bye-bye.
- Bye-bye.

946
00:52:01,418 --> 00:52:04,285
- So, Marlon, welcome back.
- How'd you do on your S.A.T.'s?

947
00:52:04,387 --> 00:52:09,518
- Uh, well, my score did not go up
the 20% you promised.
- Let's see.

948
00:52:11,328 --> 00:52:14,957
- Well, you gained 10 in math and 10 on verbal.
- That's 20. What's the problem?

949
00:52:15,065 --> 00:52:18,125
[Man] No, all kidding aside, Marlon,
you do need our help.

950
00:52:18,235 --> 00:52:21,295
- Do you have a check?
- But I need some real help.

951
00:52:21,404 --> 00:52:24,464
L... I have a chance
of getting into Ramsey.

952
00:52:24,574 --> 00:52:27,543
Marlon, academics don't necessarily
have to be your strong point.

953
00:52:27,644 --> 00:52:32,138
What you need is a hook... something for
the committee to remember you by... stand out.

954
00:52:32,249 --> 00:52:35,184
- Stick to the basics. Inner-city tutoring.
- Helping old people.

955
00:52:35,285 --> 00:52:37,845
- Environmental cleanup task force.
- Nuclear research.

956
00:52:37,954 --> 00:52:41,185
I'm not currently involved
in anything quite as interesting as that.

957
00:52:41,291 --> 00:52:43,919
For a thousand bucks, we can make
anyone's life sound interesting.

958
00:52:44,027 --> 00:52:46,587
For instance, what do you do
on a typical Saturday morning?

959
00:52:46,696 --> 00:52:49,927
Nothing. Really.
L-I baby-sit my stepbrother.

960
00:52:50,033 --> 00:52:51,967
Ah! You say nothing...

961
00:52:52,068 --> 00:52:56,061
but baby-sitting your stepbrother
is exactly the kind of mundane activity...

962
00:52:56,173 --> 00:52:59,233
that you can enhance
into a business opportunity...

963
00:52:59,342 --> 00:53:03,142
something that can really make you
stand out in the applicant pool.

964
00:53:03,246 --> 00:53:05,441
[Children Chattering]

965
00:53:08,685 --> 00:53:11,245
[Chattering]

966
00:53:21,865 --> 00:53:23,423
[Crash]

967
00:53:25,135 --> 00:53:27,899
[Crying]

968
00:53:28,004 --> 00:53:32,100
Okay, you've got work experience taken care of.
Now you want to juxtapose an unusual activity.

969
00:53:32,209 --> 00:53:34,700
Something that would wake up
a tired admissions officer at 3:00 a. M...

970
00:53:34,811 --> 00:53:36,802
like the kid who
rafted down the Amazon.

971
00:53:36,913 --> 00:53:39,279
A girl took up professional wrestling,
and she got into Yale.

972
00:53:39,382 --> 00:53:42,715
- No, Harvard.
- [Together] Thank you very much. Good-bye.

973
00:53:42,819 --> 00:53:44,980
[Both Yelling]

974
00:53:49,659 --> 00:53:51,627
[Yelling Continues]

975
00:53:55,899 --> 00:53:58,629
Hi, guys. I'm here
for the wrestling lessons.

976
00:53:58,735 --> 00:54:00,703
[Man Chuckles]

977
00:54:07,611 --> 00:54:10,774
[Cackling]

978
00:54:12,949 --> 00:54:17,648
So you want to take wrestling
as an extracurricular activity, huh?

979
00:54:17,754 --> 00:54:21,315
- [Cackling]
- No. Actually, I've been thinking it over...

980
00:54:21,424 --> 00:54:23,790
Whoa! Uh-oh. Uh-oh. Uh-oh.

981
00:54:23,893 --> 00:54:25,952
[Woman Cackling]

982
00:54:26,062 --> 00:54:28,121
[Screams, Groans]

983
00:54:28,231 --> 00:54:31,200
[Pop]

984
00:54:33,937 --> 00:54:37,338
[Man Singing]

985
00:54:45,582 --> 00:54:47,550
[Singing Continues]

986
00:55:00,497 --> 00:55:02,761
[Singing Continues]

987
00:55:11,675 --> 00:55:13,643
[Singing Continues]

988
00:55:22,652 --> 00:55:26,588
Girl, aren't you ever
gonna go home?

989
00:55:26,690 --> 00:55:29,955
I will. I just gotta
finish up this application.

990
00:55:30,060 --> 00:55:32,528
Well, don't forget
to lock up.

991
00:55:32,629 --> 00:55:34,563
- Bye, Vera.
- Good night, Henry.

992
00:55:34,664 --> 00:55:37,929
[Singing Continues]

993
00:55:52,716 --> 00:55:54,684
[Singing Continues]

994
00:56:09,766 --> 00:56:13,361
[Fades]

995
00:56:13,536 --> 00:56:16,801
- I've gotta go.
- Do you have anything for me?

996
00:56:16,906 --> 00:56:20,364
- I think this is one of yours.
- Oh, great. Marlon Browne. Good.

997
00:56:20,477 --> 00:56:22,445
[Nina Laughing]

998
00:56:22,545 --> 00:56:24,536
- That's great.
- Thanks a lot, Leo.

999
00:56:24,647 --> 00:56:27,445
All right, Nina.
Anytime. Anywhere.

1000
00:56:27,550 --> 00:56:29,780
Oh, uh...

1001
00:56:29,886 --> 00:56:32,116
[Laughing]
Oh, no.

1002
00:56:33,656 --> 00:56:36,716
[Sighs] So, did Leo give
good meeting in there?

1003
00:56:36,826 --> 00:56:40,762
We had lunch and a very serious discussion
about Vera Cooke, if you must know.

1004
00:56:40,864 --> 00:56:43,799
In fact, we've penciled in another
meeting to discuss the matter further.

1005
00:56:43,900 --> 00:56:46,892
Bet that's not all he'd like to pencil in.
[Laughs]

1006
00:56:47,003 --> 00:56:49,335
[Chuckles]
I've got work to do, Kip.

1007
00:56:49,439 --> 00:56:53,000
But keep in mind, you have as many
opportunities as Leo to become dean.

1008
00:56:53,109 --> 00:56:55,737
The only difference is
you refuse to grow up.

1009
00:57:04,354 --> 00:57:07,687
- Well, we got Marlon Browne.
- Yes.

1010
00:57:09,325 --> 00:57:11,418
Whatever happened to
Jessica Kailo?

1011
00:57:11,528 --> 00:57:13,689
I didn't apply.

1012
00:57:13,797 --> 00:57:16,357
Y-You didn't apply to Ramsey?

1013
00:57:16,466 --> 00:57:19,833
- The deadline is tonight.
- What are you, a recruiter?

1014
00:57:19,936 --> 00:57:22,928
Didn't a certain Mr. Hammett
talk to you...

1015
00:57:23,039 --> 00:57:24,973
about being perfect
Ramsey material?

1016
00:57:25,074 --> 00:57:27,133
I don't want to
talk about that, Marlon.

1017
00:57:27,243 --> 00:57:30,610
- Mr. Hammett has a warped sense of humor.
- What are you talking about?

1018
00:57:30,713 --> 00:57:32,647
He's a great guy.
It's a great school.

1019
00:57:32,749 --> 00:57:36,150
And you still have time to get your
application in. You have until 6:00 p.m.

1020
00:57:36,252 --> 00:57:38,311
Marlon...

1021
00:57:38,421 --> 00:57:41,015
Ramsey's not the right school
for me, okay?

1022
00:57:41,124 --> 00:57:43,024
- So where are you going, then?
- Michigan.

1023
00:57:43,126 --> 00:57:45,026
Your dad's school?

1024
00:57:45,128 --> 00:57:47,824
You like Michigan
better than Ramsey?

1025
00:57:47,931 --> 00:57:51,890
Look, Marlon, you couldn't possibly
understand the decisions I've had to make.

1026
00:57:52,001 --> 00:57:54,435
Maybe I couldn't, but I've made
some decisions too.

1027
00:57:54,537 --> 00:57:57,973
- I've made some very passionate decisions.
- Like what?

1028
00:57:58,074 --> 00:57:59,974
How about suiciding,
for instance?

1029
00:58:00,076 --> 00:58:02,704
I didn't apply anywhere but Ramsey,
and I don't stand a chance.

1030
00:58:02,812 --> 00:58:04,712
That's great, Marlon.
That's just crazy!

1031
00:58:04,814 --> 00:58:06,873
You're the suicide,
and I'm the one that cracked.

1032
00:58:06,983 --> 00:58:09,247
What's that make us,
weird friends or something?

1033
00:58:13,823 --> 00:58:16,758
I'm sorry, Marlon.

1034
00:58:16,860 --> 00:58:19,658
You know what I found out
when I went to Ramsey?

1035
00:58:21,431 --> 00:58:24,127
I discovered that
I'm boring and predictable...

1036
00:58:24,234 --> 00:58:26,202
that I'm totally average,
so I freaked.

1037
00:58:26,302 --> 00:58:29,362
I freaked, Marlon.

1038
00:58:29,472 --> 00:58:31,940
Then you're not average.

1039
00:58:32,041 --> 00:58:35,909
People who are average, Jessica, they don't
mind being average. They don't freak.

1040
00:58:36,012 --> 00:58:38,378
Come on, Jessica.
Don't cry.

1041
00:58:38,481 --> 00:58:40,745
Please don't cry.

1042
00:58:40,850 --> 00:58:45,048
This is why I don't talk to you a lot...
because I have this lousy effect on you.

1043
00:58:46,956 --> 00:58:48,924
[Sighs]

1044
00:58:50,527 --> 00:58:52,461
It's not you.

1045
00:58:52,562 --> 00:58:55,030
It's not?

1046
00:58:55,131 --> 00:58:57,691
No.

1047
00:58:57,800 --> 00:59:01,292
Okay, look. I think
I have an idea.

1048
00:59:03,706 --> 00:59:06,504
[Marlon] A car traveling with
two future Ramsey students...

1049
00:59:06,609 --> 00:59:10,875
must travel from hometown "A"
to college town "B"by 6:00 p.m.

1050
00:59:10,980 --> 00:59:13,915
If the distance
to travel is 450 miles...

1051
00:59:14,017 --> 00:59:16,281
and they observe
the 55 mile per hour speed limit...

1052
00:59:16,386 --> 00:59:20,049
how much time can they allow
to stop for gas and snacks?

1053
00:59:20,156 --> 00:59:23,751
None... because
six times 55 is 330.

1054
00:59:23,860 --> 00:59:26,795
We won't get to Ramsey
even if we don't stop.

1055
00:59:26,896 --> 00:59:28,796
Then how fast
should we go?

1056
00:59:28,898 --> 00:59:32,356
Well, let's make it easy.
Six times 60 is 360.

1057
00:59:32,468 --> 00:59:34,527
Thirty minutes to spare
should be enough time.

1058
00:59:34,637 --> 00:59:38,232
- So, we, uh...
- We go 60, Marlon.

1059
00:59:38,341 --> 00:59:41,003
- Go 60.
- Got it.

1060
00:59:41,110 --> 00:59:43,943
[Woman Singing]

1061
00:59:53,389 --> 00:59:56,552
- How long did it take you to write your essay?
- I didn't write one.

1062
00:59:56,659 --> 00:59:59,958
- I sent in a video instead.
- Sounds so creative.

1063
01:00:00,063 --> 01:00:02,258
I had to do something, you know?
I spent all this...

1064
01:00:02,365 --> 01:00:04,265
time and money
going to these consultants.

1065
01:00:04,367 --> 01:00:08,167
The only helpful thing I got from them was you
have to get the attention of admissions.

1066
01:00:08,271 --> 01:00:11,206
They want to know who you are.
So I made this video.

1067
01:00:11,307 --> 01:00:12,968
That's great, Marlon.

1068
01:00:13,076 --> 01:00:16,534
[Singing Continues]

1069
01:00:25,989 --> 01:00:28,685
[Keyboard Keys Clacking]

1070
01:00:28,791 --> 01:00:30,691
- [Horn Honks]
- Whoa!

1071
01:00:30,793 --> 01:00:32,693
- A turtle! Gopher.
- A gopher or a turtle?

1072
01:00:32,795 --> 01:00:35,127
Yes, that's what it was.
It was a rare gopher-turtle.

1073
01:00:35,231 --> 01:00:38,792
- [Chuckles] Oh, okay.
- Mm-hmm.

1074
01:00:38,901 --> 01:00:42,200
- All right, here's my opening, all right?
- Yeah.

1075
01:00:42,305 --> 01:00:44,967
Okay. "I want to go
to Ramsey and be rude.

1076
01:00:45,074 --> 01:00:47,542
"Not because I don't like people
and not all the time...

1077
01:00:47,644 --> 01:00:50,636
"but if I'm walking across campus
one day contemplating Aristotle...

1078
01:00:50,747 --> 01:00:54,012
"I won't worry if people think I'm a snob
if I don't smile and say hi to them.

1079
01:00:54,117 --> 01:00:56,051
I did enough
of that in high school."

1080
01:00:56,152 --> 01:00:58,313
- I think it's great.
- Yeah?

1081
01:00:58,421 --> 01:01:01,219
- It's excellent.
- Do you want to hear the title?

1082
01:01:01,324 --> 01:01:04,191
"Secret Confessions
of a High School Prom Queen."

1083
01:01:04,293 --> 01:01:06,386
- Oh!
- Yeah? You like it? It works?

1084
01:01:06,496 --> 01:01:08,521
It's definitely gonna
brighten the lives...

1085
01:01:08,631 --> 01:01:11,156
of any admissions officer
and his children.

1086
01:01:11,267 --> 01:01:13,531
[Scoffs] All right.
On to paragraph two.

1087
01:01:13,636 --> 01:01:16,196
[Singing Continues]

1088
01:01:17,306 --> 01:01:19,604
[Fades]

1089
01:01:19,709 --> 01:01:21,506
Look. You think
you can make it?

1090
01:01:21,611 --> 01:01:24,102
- Yeah. I'm almost ready to print.
- What is with these trucks?

1091
01:01:24,213 --> 01:01:26,044
I thought these guys
were all on amphetamines.

1092
01:01:26,149 --> 01:01:29,778
- Just what we need.
- Oh, it's a cop.

1093
01:01:29,886 --> 01:01:31,683
Shit! He's doing
the speed limit.

1094
01:01:31,788 --> 01:01:34,848
Marlon, we can't go 55.
It'll blow the whole equation.

1095
01:01:34,957 --> 01:01:36,686
[Horn Honking]

1096
01:01:37,894 --> 01:01:40,124
- [Marlon] Great.
- Wonderful.

1097
01:01:40,229 --> 01:01:43,756
According to the map, a road
intersects this one in 22 miles.

1098
01:01:43,866 --> 01:01:46,926
If the cop takes that road,
leaving us with 32 miles left to travel...

1099
01:01:47,036 --> 01:01:48,936
how fast would
we have to go?

1100
01:01:49,038 --> 01:01:51,370
Do we wanna know the time
or distance in this problem?

1101
01:01:51,474 --> 01:01:55,410
Don't panic. Let's just
be logical about this.

1102
01:01:55,511 --> 01:01:57,706
Let's go slower.

1103
01:01:57,814 --> 01:02:01,978
Slower? Marlon, this is logical
on what planet?

1104
01:02:02,085 --> 01:02:05,748
- [Horn Honks]
- Come on. Come on. Come on.

1105
01:02:05,855 --> 01:02:07,652
Go for it!

1106
01:02:10,059 --> 01:02:12,926
- Whoo!
- [Marlon] Moron.

1107
01:02:13,029 --> 01:02:15,327
- [Siren Whirring]
- [Laughs]

1108
01:02:19,669 --> 01:02:22,502
I always knew that S.A. T. Stuff
wouldn't help much in real life.

1109
01:02:24,006 --> 01:02:27,169
[Horn Honks]

1110
01:02:32,115 --> 01:02:34,583
You asshole.

1111
01:03:00,076 --> 01:03:03,375
No. Why is it locked?
Is it 6:00 already?

1112
01:03:03,479 --> 01:03:06,937
No. It's five to 6:00.
It's not fair.

1113
01:03:07,049 --> 01:03:10,610
Hey, Jessica, are you the kind of girl
whose dad gave her a credit card?

1114
01:03:10,720 --> 01:03:12,711
Yeah,
but it's expired.

1115
01:03:12,822 --> 01:03:16,690
Doesn't matter, because membership
has its advantages.

1116
01:03:20,096 --> 01:03:22,530
Wait.
Somebody's coming.

1117
01:03:25,735 --> 01:03:29,933
[Door Handle Rattles]

1118
01:03:38,815 --> 01:03:41,545
I think he's gone.

1119
01:03:43,085 --> 01:03:46,452
Okay. Over here.
Over here. Okay.

1120
01:03:48,291 --> 01:03:51,488
I can't believe we're breaking and entering
the college we want to get into.

1121
01:03:53,129 --> 01:03:55,563
[Kisses]
For good luck.

1122
01:03:57,366 --> 01:03:59,266
[Kisses]

1123
01:04:17,053 --> 01:04:19,954
Well, we made it.
All we can do now is wait.

1124
01:04:20,056 --> 01:04:23,787
Yeah.
[Exhales]

1125
01:04:26,796 --> 01:04:29,458
- Marlon?
- Yes, Jessica?

1126
01:04:31,300 --> 01:04:33,700
I don't know. I just wanted
to say thanks for everything.

1127
01:04:33,803 --> 01:04:36,363
I really hope
we both get into Ramsey.

1128
01:04:36,472 --> 01:04:40,067
I couldn't think of a nicer guy to spend
the next four years of my life with.

1129
01:04:53,322 --> 01:04:56,120
Well, let's not rule out
graduate school.

1130
01:04:58,194 --> 01:05:01,095
- [Chuckles]
- Good night, Marlon.

1131
01:05:01,197 --> 01:05:03,392
Good night.

1132
01:05:08,170 --> 01:05:10,070
[Sighs]

1133
01:05:15,411 --> 01:05:17,311
[Horn Honking]

1134
01:05:17,413 --> 01:05:19,313
That's right,
boys and girls...

1135
01:05:19,415 --> 01:05:21,940
get your college paraphernalia
while it's hot.

1136
01:05:22,051 --> 01:05:25,020
It's okay, Mom.
Just describe the envelope to me.

1137
01:05:25,121 --> 01:05:27,021
Well, is it fat or what?

1138
01:05:27,123 --> 01:05:29,091
Just tell me, Mom.
Is it fat or skinny?

1139
01:05:29,191 --> 01:05:31,386
Mom, just tell me.
Is the envelope big or small?

1140
01:05:31,494 --> 01:05:33,394
Mom, God!
Just...

1141
01:05:33,496 --> 01:05:35,589
I got accepted into Michigan.
So big deal, right?

1142
01:05:35,698 --> 01:05:37,427
I wouldn't care at all,
except for Kelly.

1143
01:05:37,533 --> 01:05:40,093
She was rejected by
six schools already.

1144
01:05:40,202 --> 01:05:42,898
[Sobs]
Seven schools!

1145
01:05:44,740 --> 01:05:48,301
That's why I recommend suiciding.
You can only get rejected once.

1146
01:05:48,411 --> 01:05:52,279
This waiting around here for Ramsey's
killing me. I wish I could have Amy's cool.

1147
01:05:52,381 --> 01:05:55,748
Just talk to me, goddamn it!
Is it fat or what?

1148
01:05:55,851 --> 01:05:59,116
Fat or skinny?
[Screams] I'll kill her!

1149
01:05:59,221 --> 01:06:03,351
Here's an interesting case.
Vera Cooke.

1150
01:06:04,894 --> 01:06:06,794
She is, as far as I know...

1151
01:06:06,896 --> 01:06:09,763
the most underprivileged youngster
that we have this year.

1152
01:06:09,865 --> 01:06:12,356
She's got, uh... Oh, thanks, Leo.
She's got decent grades.

1153
01:06:12,468 --> 01:06:14,368
Her father
is out of the picture.

1154
01:06:14,470 --> 01:06:17,405
No, her father's dead.
She wrote about him in her essay.

1155
01:06:17,506 --> 01:06:20,031
Oh. Oh, yes.
Oh, and it says here...

1156
01:06:20,142 --> 01:06:23,475
"Her energy and struggle to obtain
her dreams has produced an individual...

1157
01:06:23,579 --> 01:06:25,069
"both tough and sweet.

1158
01:06:25,181 --> 01:06:28,639
She's a woman and a girl
to reckon with and to love."

1159
01:06:28,751 --> 01:06:33,017
[Scoffs] Geez! Who writes this crap?
Lionel Richie?

1160
01:06:33,122 --> 01:06:36,091
- I wrote it.
- You know, I met him once.

1161
01:06:36,192 --> 01:06:39,059
- He's a lovely man if you meet him in person.
- This is Vera Cooke.

1162
01:06:39,161 --> 01:06:42,096
- We discussed her, remember?
- Oh, yeah.

1163
01:06:42,198 --> 01:06:45,929
I recruited Vera, and I strongly
recommend her to this committee.

1164
01:06:46,035 --> 01:06:49,004
- How are her college boards?
- Well, she's 410 verbal, 470 math.

1165
01:06:49,105 --> 01:06:53,098
The point is that's not the kind of question
we need to be asking about a person like Vera.

1166
01:06:53,209 --> 01:06:57,270
- What is the right question?
- Whether we, as a group,
are willing to take a chance.

1167
01:06:57,380 --> 01:07:00,406
This is a case in which Ramsey
can make a difference, one that...

1168
01:07:00,516 --> 01:07:02,245
could actually change
someone's life.

1169
01:07:02,351 --> 01:07:04,046
We all agree
with Nina, right?

1170
01:07:04,153 --> 01:07:08,351
During the break, I talked to Leo.
He brought up an interesting point.

1171
01:07:08,457 --> 01:07:10,357
Whose interests
are we serving here?

1172
01:07:10,459 --> 01:07:13,758
Ramsey is a very
competitive environment.

1173
01:07:13,863 --> 01:07:17,026
We need minority students,
but at the expense of this girl?

1174
01:07:17,133 --> 01:07:20,728
I don't see that we're really
that desperate to fill our quota.

1175
01:07:20,836 --> 01:07:23,634
Forget the quota.
Forget she's black.

1176
01:07:23,739 --> 01:07:26,139
Good. My vote can't be won
on the basis of color.

1177
01:07:26,242 --> 01:07:29,370
So what does that leave us with
as far as Vera Cooke is concerned...

1178
01:07:29,478 --> 01:07:32,936
- aside from the dismal numbers?
- Everything that's not a number.

1179
01:07:33,049 --> 01:07:36,314
What's the commitment
to deserving students in this room?

1180
01:07:36,419 --> 01:07:39,547
Oh, please. I mean, we've got
top-notch minority applicants from...

1181
01:07:39,655 --> 01:07:42,522
- Andover, uh, Phillips Exeter...
- Oh, this is completely outrageous, Leo.

1182
01:07:42,625 --> 01:07:45,458
You know exactly how I feel
about giving this girl a chance.

1183
01:07:45,561 --> 01:07:48,792
I think we all want
a reasonable solution. Leo?

1184
01:07:48,898 --> 01:07:53,164
Well, I have no objections to the wait list.
Sally, how do you feel about that?

1185
01:07:53,269 --> 01:07:56,602
The w... The wait list? That's like
falling into bureaucratic limbo.

1186
01:07:56,705 --> 01:07:59,003
Nobody ever gets in here
on the wait list.

1187
01:07:59,108 --> 01:08:01,372
Can we, uh, move on, please?

1188
01:08:19,728 --> 01:08:23,255
Oh, my God.

1189
01:08:23,365 --> 01:08:25,595
It's from Ramsey.

1190
01:08:27,436 --> 01:08:29,870
Oh, it is.

1191
01:08:29,972 --> 01:08:31,963
Somebody's gotta open it.

1192
01:08:34,376 --> 01:08:36,640
I'll do it.

1193
01:08:47,156 --> 01:08:49,386
[Crying]

1194
01:08:53,195 --> 01:08:56,790
I'm so happy for you.
[Sobbing]

1195
01:09:00,903 --> 01:09:03,371
You did it!
You got into Ramsey.

1196
01:09:03,472 --> 01:09:06,908
- You did it.
- But what about Marlon Browne?

1197
01:09:10,079 --> 01:09:13,776
[Laughs]
Sixty, 70, 80, 90...

1198
01:09:13,883 --> 01:09:16,044
You look like a guy
who's obviously gonna make it.

1199
01:09:16,152 --> 01:09:19,451
I'd better. I paid
a thousand bucks to Bauer-Benedek.

1200
01:09:19,555 --> 01:09:22,183
They said stuff like this
would look great on my application.

1201
01:09:22,291 --> 01:09:24,691
Did you hear
anything yet?

1202
01:09:24,793 --> 01:09:28,024
Hey, cheer up.
Have a bumper sticker on me.

1203
01:09:29,498 --> 01:09:32,058
- [Laughs]
- [Horn Honks]

1204
01:09:33,903 --> 01:09:36,804
Come on, Ramsey.
What's going on?

1205
01:09:40,509 --> 01:09:42,500
Now, I know this kid
seems hopeless on paper...

1206
01:09:42,611 --> 01:09:44,511
but you gotta
see this tape.

1207
01:09:44,613 --> 01:09:47,514
Now, I met him, and I think
he's really got somethin'.

1208
01:09:47,616 --> 01:09:51,245
Oh, yeah? Better be
a union card.

1209
01:09:51,353 --> 01:09:53,253
I don't know, Bob.

1210
01:09:53,355 --> 01:09:55,687
Do we really have time
for this kind of tomfoolery?

1211
01:09:55,791 --> 01:09:59,955
[Bob] Well, we are running late,
and tomorrow is the last day of admissions.

1212
01:10:00,062 --> 01:10:04,055
There are just so many openings left. I don't
think this boy's folder warrants the time.

1213
01:10:04,166 --> 01:10:07,431
We used to have time
for all types of kids.

1214
01:10:07,536 --> 01:10:10,369
- I'd like to see the tape.
- You could give Flutter the tape.

1215
01:10:10,472 --> 01:10:13,270
I'm not gonna look at it.
Besides, we gave you the Kailo girl.

1216
01:10:13,375 --> 01:10:16,071
- Remember?
- No, Leo, you didn't give me anything.

1217
01:10:16,178 --> 01:10:18,646
I mean, we're supposed to find
interesting students.

1218
01:10:18,747 --> 01:10:21,079
Now, I think Marlon Browne
is one of them.

1219
01:10:21,183 --> 01:10:23,981
Take another look
at Mr. Video's numbers.

1220
01:10:24,086 --> 01:10:28,546
I don't know, Bob. I've gotta give this kid
two thumbs down on the Ramsey scale.

1221
01:10:28,657 --> 01:10:33,060
Dean, I think it's a tragedy if we're saying
that the era of the still-searching...

1222
01:10:33,162 --> 01:10:37,292
doesn't-know-exactly-
what-to-do-with-his-life kid
is over here at Ramsey.

1223
01:10:37,399 --> 01:10:40,368
Yeah, well, it's canceled, all right,
due to poor ratings.

1224
01:10:40,469 --> 01:10:42,733
- Do you understand, Hammett?
- Yeah, I get it, Leo.

1225
01:10:42,838 --> 01:10:45,932
You got a new program...
Leo, Dean of Admissions.

1226
01:10:46,041 --> 01:10:48,271
You know, I think
I'd watch that show.

1227
01:10:48,377 --> 01:10:51,346
Well, I'm not gonna watch it
because with Leo, Dean of Admissions...

1228
01:10:51,447 --> 01:10:54,814
calling the shots around here,
myjob description sucks.

1229
01:10:54,917 --> 01:10:58,910
I don't wanna stay around here
and watch you ruin a place I love.

1230
01:11:02,124 --> 01:11:06,083
So, Nina, looks like your lunch
schedule's opening wide up.

1231
01:11:06,195 --> 01:11:08,493
Screw you, Leo.
Excuse me.

1232
01:11:11,066 --> 01:11:14,194
[Door Closes]

1233
01:11:14,303 --> 01:11:16,271
[Door Opens, Closes]

1234
01:11:20,676 --> 01:11:23,144
Will you show me
Marlon's tape?

1235
01:11:23,245 --> 01:11:25,713
Yeah. Sure.

1236
01:11:25,814 --> 01:11:27,941
- Come on in.
- [Chuckles]

1237
01:11:28,050 --> 01:11:30,917
Hi. I'm Marlon Browne,
and you wouldn't believe...

1238
01:11:31,020 --> 01:11:33,818
all the stuff I did
trying to get into college.

1239
01:11:33,922 --> 01:11:36,322
Looking back, the juggling
seems really pathetic.

1240
01:11:36,425 --> 01:11:40,259
I know it was a creative activity
to put on my application and all...

1241
01:11:40,362 --> 01:11:43,422
but I can't believe tossing
flaming sticks in the air...

1242
01:11:43,532 --> 01:11:46,729
is gonna qualify me as
an interesting guy to have on campus.

1243
01:11:46,835 --> 01:11:50,464
- [Stick Falls, Rattles]
- I felt I had to do something unusual...

1244
01:11:50,572 --> 01:11:53,234
- [Cackles]
- [Marlon] But intramural, professional wrestling...

1245
01:11:53,342 --> 01:11:55,401
was never a workable idea.

1246
01:11:55,511 --> 01:11:58,309
[Yells, Grunts]

1247
01:11:58,414 --> 01:12:00,882
- [Laughing]
- [Yelling Continues]

1248
01:12:07,656 --> 01:12:11,023
[Marlon Narrating] I was desperate.
Everywhere I went, people told me...

1249
01:12:11,126 --> 01:12:13,594
how competitive it is to get
into college these days.

1250
01:12:13,696 --> 01:12:16,460
Here's some advice,
Marlon.

1251
01:12:16,565 --> 01:12:20,023
- Hope for a miracle.
- That'll be $100.

1252
01:12:20,135 --> 01:12:23,571
[Marlon Narrating] I came face to face
with the truth after my business failed.

1253
01:12:23,672 --> 01:12:25,731
I got it, you guys.
Come on. Let's go!

1254
01:12:28,610 --> 01:12:30,578
Grow up, Marlon.

1255
01:12:32,281 --> 01:12:35,045
"Grow up."
That really got to me.

1256
01:12:35,150 --> 01:12:38,950
It's something people tell me a lot.
And what am I supposed to answer?

1257
01:12:39,054 --> 01:12:41,614
I'm growing
as fast as I can?

1258
01:12:41,724 --> 01:12:44,591
Which brings me
to the point of my story.

1259
01:12:44,693 --> 01:12:48,220
- Time to mature is what I need. Right, Willie?
- Right.

1260
01:12:48,330 --> 01:12:50,230
Marlon's a great kid,
really.

1261
01:12:50,332 --> 01:12:54,132
He just... He needs a little time
to develop, like a fine wine.

1262
01:12:54,236 --> 01:12:56,864
If you give me a chance,
I will be the most...

1263
01:12:56,972 --> 01:13:00,430
enthusiastic, open-minded
student you have ever seen at Ramsey.

1264
01:13:00,542 --> 01:13:03,443
- We could really use the room.
- [Laughs]

1265
01:13:03,545 --> 01:13:07,641
Come on, Marlon.
Time for your next lesson.

1266
01:13:07,750 --> 01:13:10,218
Well, gotta go.

1267
01:13:10,319 --> 01:13:13,482
Please, consider me for Ramsey.
I won't let you down.

1268
01:13:14,590 --> 01:13:17,388
- Leo's a pig.
- [Chuckles]

1269
01:13:17,493 --> 01:13:19,393
Leo is six pigs.

1270
01:13:19,495 --> 01:13:23,261
- [Laughs]
- Oh, God, I think I just got an idea.

1271
01:13:26,068 --> 01:13:28,969
[Dog Barking, Growling]

1272
01:13:40,416 --> 01:13:42,646
You. You're the mailman.

1273
01:13:42,751 --> 01:13:44,946
Yeah.

1274
01:13:46,321 --> 01:13:48,289
Who's it for?

1275
01:13:48,390 --> 01:13:50,915
[Barking, Growling Continues]

1276
01:13:51,026 --> 01:13:53,392
- Are you Marlon Browne?
- Yes.

1277
01:13:53,495 --> 01:13:56,020
- It's for you.
- Where's it from?

1278
01:13:58,534 --> 01:14:01,662
- Pennsylvania.
- Pennsylvania.

1279
01:14:01,770 --> 01:14:04,637
Ramsey, Pennsylvania.
Would you do me a favor and open it?

1280
01:14:04,740 --> 01:14:06,640
I can't look.
L-I'm too nervous.

1281
01:14:06,742 --> 01:14:08,710
I'd love to.

1282
01:14:17,085 --> 01:14:20,111
- Marlon Browne?
- Yes.

1283
01:14:20,222 --> 01:14:22,053
Congratulations.

1284
01:14:22,157 --> 01:14:24,887
I did it? I got into Ramsey?
It's from Ramsey?

1285
01:14:24,993 --> 01:14:26,824
No. It's from Ed McMahon.

1286
01:14:26,929 --> 01:14:30,956
You may have already
won $ 10 million.

1287
01:14:35,304 --> 01:14:39,001
I get the feeling we could double our
endowment if we get a stronger student body...

1288
01:14:39,107 --> 01:14:42,975
Leo, I believe this folder
escaped your attention.

1289
01:14:43,078 --> 01:14:45,979
Thank you, Sally.

1290
01:14:47,483 --> 01:14:50,145
Well, look who
just walked in.

1291
01:14:50,252 --> 01:14:52,686
Mr. Grumpy decide
to finish his tenure?

1292
01:14:52,788 --> 01:14:56,815
- Good to have you back, Kip.
- Last chance to admit the reject du jour, Kip.

1293
01:14:56,925 --> 01:14:58,859
No, no.
That's your department, Leo.

1294
01:14:58,961 --> 01:15:00,826
Au contraire, Kipster.

1295
01:15:00,929 --> 01:15:04,558
It's the likes of Leonard Edward Funt
that catch my eye.

1296
01:15:04,666 --> 01:15:08,102
Listen to these numbers...
800 verbal, 760 math...

1297
01:15:08,203 --> 01:15:10,103
4.0 G.P.A.

1298
01:15:10,205 --> 01:15:12,332
Second-ranked
in his class.

1299
01:15:12,441 --> 01:15:17,105
I wonder which sophomoric admissions officer
kept this kid a secret. Kip?

1300
01:15:17,212 --> 01:15:21,342
Leo, let me see that. I don't remember
hearing about this folder.

1301
01:15:21,450 --> 01:15:23,077
- Who were the readers?
- I was.

1302
01:15:23,185 --> 01:15:25,517
- [Chuckles] That figures.
- Oh, you too, Leo.

1303
01:15:25,621 --> 01:15:27,452
Me and Flutter?

1304
01:15:27,556 --> 01:15:29,581
- [Bob] Mm-hmm.
- Let me see that folder.

1305
01:15:31,159 --> 01:15:33,093
Excuse me, Leo.

1306
01:15:33,195 --> 01:15:35,129
Good Lord, Leo,
your comments are right here.

1307
01:15:35,230 --> 01:15:37,960
"Leonard Edward Funt
is a first-rate specimen.

1308
01:15:38,066 --> 01:15:41,035
- Don't let him slip away."
- [Leo] And I meant it.

1309
01:15:41,136 --> 01:15:44,071
I mean, just looking at
those numbers makes my mouth water.

1310
01:15:44,172 --> 01:15:46,800
I say we send a limo
unless Kip has an argument.

1311
01:15:46,909 --> 01:15:49,434
- What the hell.
- Thank you, Kip.

1312
01:16:02,524 --> 01:16:05,891
Now, as the new dean, I'm gonna
be making just a few changes.

1313
01:16:05,994 --> 01:16:08,963
First of all, I'll be getting
a new paint job for the old Beemer.

1314
01:16:09,064 --> 01:16:10,964
So I'm gonna need
two parking spaces.

1315
01:16:11,066 --> 01:16:14,194
I might have to bump you
to the custodial parking lot. You mind?

1316
01:16:14,303 --> 01:16:16,635
Okay, Leo.
Anything you say.

1317
01:16:16,738 --> 01:16:18,638
I'm beginning
to like you, Flutter.

1318
01:16:18,740 --> 01:16:21,174
Maybe I won't move your office
down to the basement.

1319
01:16:21,276 --> 01:16:23,176
Leo...

1320
01:16:23,278 --> 01:16:28,011
Uh, Mr. Funt has arrived, and Kip
thought you might wanna say hello.

1321
01:16:28,116 --> 01:16:32,519
Leonard Edward Funt,
the new pride of Ramsey?

1322
01:16:32,621 --> 01:16:36,148
Now we're gonna see the kind of student
we should be admitting to Ramsey.

1323
01:16:37,559 --> 01:16:39,925
Now, Dean, I'm sure
you'll enjoy meeting...

1324
01:16:40,028 --> 01:16:43,759
the kind of students
we should be admitting here at Ramsey.

1325
01:16:43,865 --> 01:16:46,356
Students which I, as your successor,
would be very proud...

1326
01:16:46,468 --> 01:16:48,368
to provide
for these hallowed halls.

1327
01:16:48,470 --> 01:16:50,961
Leonard E. Funt
is one of my personal prides.

1328
01:16:51,073 --> 01:16:53,041
- Leonard.
- [Flutter Chuckling]

1329
01:16:53,141 --> 01:16:54,802
What is this thing?

1330
01:16:54,910 --> 01:16:57,276
It's not a thing, Leo.
It's a pachyderm.

1331
01:16:57,379 --> 01:16:58,937
L.E. Funt.

1332
01:16:59,047 --> 01:17:01,140
The new pride of Ramsey.
[Chuckles]

1333
01:17:01,249 --> 01:17:04,184
Leonard... Edward.
"El-ee-funt."

1334
01:17:04,286 --> 01:17:06,982
Bob, please. You've got
to agree with me...

1335
01:17:07,089 --> 01:17:10,684
that this prank is not
gonna look good on Hammett's record.

1336
01:17:10,792 --> 01:17:12,885
What are you talking about?
I quit, remember?

1337
01:17:12,995 --> 01:17:15,987
After fighting a losing battle
to admit a few good human beings.

1338
01:17:16,098 --> 01:17:18,566
What's this?

1339
01:17:18,667 --> 01:17:23,001
This is a filthy beast and a stupid prank,
compliments of Kip Hammett.

1340
01:17:23,105 --> 01:17:27,007
- Oh, and me.
- Don't tell me this is Leonard Edward Funt.

1341
01:17:27,109 --> 01:17:29,168
Yes, it is, Chancellor.

1342
01:17:29,277 --> 01:17:31,302
- Joanna.
- [Sally Chuckles]

1343
01:17:31,413 --> 01:17:34,780
He's got the perfect numbers. If these
standards had been used when I applied...

1344
01:17:34,883 --> 01:17:36,783
you never
would have admitted me.

1345
01:17:36,885 --> 01:17:39,149
And I think Ramsey and I
were a perfect match.

1346
01:17:39,254 --> 01:17:41,722
So do I.

1347
01:17:41,823 --> 01:17:43,848
That's all we wanted to say.
So good luck.

1348
01:17:45,127 --> 01:17:47,891
- See you later.
- Wait!

1349
01:17:47,996 --> 01:17:52,228
Maybe we've gone overboard, Leo.
Yes. I think they're right.

1350
01:17:52,334 --> 01:17:54,529
What do you suggest
we do about this, Kip?

1351
01:17:54,636 --> 01:17:58,663
Well, uh, we do have
a couple of suggestions.

1352
01:18:00,809 --> 01:18:03,039
What about Leonard?
Is he going to Ramsey?

1353
01:18:03,145 --> 01:18:07,013
Flutter, with Leonard's numbers,
he's got his heart set on Harvard.

1354
01:18:07,115 --> 01:18:09,515
[Laughing]

1355
01:18:09,618 --> 01:18:12,280
- [Laughs]
- [Growls]

1356
01:18:12,387 --> 01:18:14,719
[Laughs]

1357
01:18:16,658 --> 01:18:19,752
Here, Leo. Have a happy future.
[Laughs]

1358
01:18:21,196 --> 01:18:23,858
- [Lapping Water]
- [Squealing]

1359
01:18:26,668 --> 01:18:29,330
So, Leonard...

1360
01:18:29,438 --> 01:18:31,039
Harvard, huh?

1361
01:18:31,039 --> 01:18:31,596
Harvard, huh?

1362
01:18:32,708 --> 01:18:35,268
[Man Vocalizing]

1363
01:18:39,681 --> 01:18:42,275
Thank you.
Have a nice day. Come again.

1364
01:18:44,352 --> 01:18:46,252
It's from Ramsey.

1365
01:18:48,123 --> 01:18:50,057
I'm too scared, Ma.
You open it.

1366
01:18:50,158 --> 01:18:52,319
[Vocalizing Continues]

1367
01:18:55,597 --> 01:18:58,225
[Man Singing]

1368
01:19:01,903 --> 01:19:03,803
You did it, baby.

1369
01:19:06,775 --> 01:19:08,675
I did it?

1370
01:19:08,777 --> 01:19:10,836
I got in?

1371
01:19:10,946 --> 01:19:14,746
- I got into college!
- [Cheering]

1372
01:19:17,619 --> 01:19:19,644
[Singing Continues]

1373
01:19:21,923 --> 01:19:24,187
It's from Ramsey.

1374
01:19:31,166 --> 01:19:34,693
- I got accepted.
- I got rejected.

1375
01:19:34,803 --> 01:19:38,204
- Bummer.
- What's yours say?

1376
01:19:38,306 --> 01:19:40,536
It says, "Dear Laurie...

1377
01:19:40,642 --> 01:19:43,770
"congratulations on your acceptance
at Ramsey College...

1378
01:19:43,879 --> 01:19:47,474
and we look forward
to your... violin playing."

1379
01:19:47,582 --> 01:19:50,380
You play the oboe.
I play the violin.

1380
01:19:50,485 --> 01:19:52,385
[Together]
Shit.

1381
01:19:57,359 --> 01:20:00,920
Look, hon,
it's from Ramsey.

1382
01:20:03,231 --> 01:20:07,190
Another wait list.
Shall we file it with the rest?

1383
01:20:09,337 --> 01:20:11,567
Your mother and I
are making a fire.

1384
01:20:11,673 --> 01:20:13,664
[Sobbing]

1385
01:20:13,775 --> 01:20:16,039
[Singing Continues]

1386
01:20:19,014 --> 01:20:21,414
[Singing Continues]

1387
01:20:30,959 --> 01:20:33,291
What happened?

1388
01:20:35,130 --> 01:20:37,030
I got into Ramsey.

1389
01:20:37,132 --> 01:20:39,657
Congratulations.

1390
01:20:41,269 --> 01:20:43,260
You're going through with it, huh?
You're leaving?

1391
01:20:43,371 --> 01:20:45,430
I'll send you
postcards, Browne.

1392
01:20:45,540 --> 01:20:48,998
I got a lot of miles to cover,
and it all starts with the first step.

1393
01:20:49,110 --> 01:20:51,408
- Don't forget me.
- Not in a million years.

1394
01:20:51,513 --> 01:20:53,777
[Singing Continues]

1395
01:20:58,153 --> 01:21:00,246
[Woman Giggling]

1396
01:21:03,158 --> 01:21:07,254
So, which direction
are you headed?

1397
01:21:07,362 --> 01:21:10,422
We're traveling the world
with unclaimed game show prizes.

1398
01:21:10,532 --> 01:21:12,557
Oh, Bob, can we
take him with us? Please, Bob?

1399
01:21:12,667 --> 01:21:15,465
- Please!
- Please, Bob. Take me with you.

1400
01:21:15,570 --> 01:21:18,596
- Oh, what the heck. Hop in, kid.
- [Giggles]

1401
01:21:24,880 --> 01:21:27,849
[Vocalizing]

1402
01:21:29,818 --> 01:21:31,786
- Here he comes now.
- Ronny! Ronny!

1403
01:21:31,887 --> 01:21:36,153
I would just like to say we are so proud
to be signing here at Ramsey College.

1404
01:21:36,258 --> 01:21:38,783
- I mean, we're just thrilled...
- Yo, chill, baby.

1405
01:21:41,529 --> 01:21:44,259
Football is a great game...

1406
01:21:44,366 --> 01:21:46,266
but it's only a game.

1407
01:21:46,368 --> 01:21:48,893
I think it was Plato
who said it best when he said...

1408
01:21:49,004 --> 01:21:51,734
"The unexamined life
is not worth living."

1409
01:21:51,840 --> 01:21:55,105
I'm grateful to the Ramsey football staff
for its support...

1410
01:21:55,210 --> 01:21:58,236
but I've decided
to dedicate my time here...

1411
01:21:58,346 --> 01:22:02,305
to more...
intellectual pursuits.

1412
01:22:02,417 --> 01:22:05,113
Thank you.

1413
01:22:05,220 --> 01:22:07,415
[Crowd Murmuring]

1414
01:22:09,391 --> 01:22:11,359
[Sobbing]

1415
01:22:12,727 --> 01:22:14,627
Nice office.

1416
01:22:14,729 --> 01:22:16,890
Was it always this big?

1417
01:22:16,998 --> 01:22:19,694
Did it always have
this many windows?

1418
01:22:19,801 --> 01:22:22,634
You're so impressed
with the trappings of power.

1419
01:22:22,737 --> 01:22:25,365
I'm so impressed
with powerful men.

1420
01:22:26,875 --> 01:22:31,073
- Yeah.
- Did it always have the leather couch?

1421
01:22:33,915 --> 01:22:36,611
[Chuckles]

1422
01:22:36,718 --> 01:22:38,743
[Vocalizing]

1423
01:22:38,853 --> 01:22:42,016
[Fades]

1424
01:22:43,158 --> 01:22:45,683
[Laughs]

1425
01:22:51,399 --> 01:22:55,062
Two men, "A" and "B",
are trapped inside my mailbox...

1426
01:22:55,170 --> 01:22:57,502
chained to 200,000 pounds
of explosives.

1427
01:22:57,605 --> 01:22:59,505
This isn't funny,
Marlon!

1428
01:22:59,607 --> 01:23:01,837
Come on, man.
What test is this?

1429
01:23:01,943 --> 01:23:04,639
- Cut it out, Marlon!
- If the chains are three inches thick...

1430
01:23:04,746 --> 01:23:08,307
and they have 30 seconds to escape,
sawing at one inch per second...

1431
01:23:08,416 --> 01:23:09,906
what are their
chances of survival?

1432
01:23:10,018 --> 01:23:13,044
Go on to the next question,
Marlon! Go on! Skip it!

1433
01:23:13,154 --> 01:23:17,250
Come on, man! Get us out of here!
Answer the question!

1434
01:23:17,359 --> 01:23:21,352
Who cares? I already
got into college. [Chuckles]

1435
01:23:21,463 --> 01:23:23,832
Hey, who do you think
you're kidding?

1436
01:23:23,898 --> 01:23:25,798
[Screams]
We're gonna die.!

1437
01:23:25,900 --> 01:23:28,266
["B"] We're not gonna die.
Marlon wouldn't kill us.

1438
01:23:28,370 --> 01:23:30,838
["A"] What are you talking about?
We're in a mailbox.!

1439
01:23:30,939 --> 01:23:33,499
["B"] Come on, Marlon.
Let us out.!

1440
01:23:33,608 --> 01:23:36,202
You made it.

1441
01:23:37,746 --> 01:23:40,579
Great. You made it.
[Chuckles]

1442
01:23:43,418 --> 01:23:46,046
["A"] There's always
graduate school.!

1443
01:23:56,398 --> 01:23:59,799
[Man Singing]

1444
01:26:47,335 --> 01:26:49,769
[Fades]

